00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:04.610
The theme of gender
and language makes

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:08.220
something of a departure
from many of the topics

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:12.000
that our gender conferences
have tackled in the past.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.079
In recent years, we've explored
gender and the public's health,

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:19.649
gender and migration,
gender and violence,

00:04:19.649 --> 00:04:22.060
and women and democracy,
and perhaps some of you

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:24.600
have been here for those events.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:28.020
These are all topics with
obvious public policy

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:29.240
relevance.

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:34.350
In contrast, today's conference,
which focuses on language

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:37.990
as a fluid reflection
of cultural practices,

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:41.700
might at first seem
to be more abstract.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:44.220
But the truth is that
we are surrounded

00:04:44.220 --> 00:04:48.500
by questions of gender
and language all the time.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:51.930
Right now, for example, a
writer in our fellowship program

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:54.980
is working on a novel
with a transgender person

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:57.450
as one of the
central characters.

00:04:57.450 --> 00:04:59.620
And as we look
ahead to next year,

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:02.230
Jennifer Finney Boylan,
author and advocate

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:04.680
for transgender rights,
will be delivering

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:06.620
a lecture in February.

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:09.490
And this is not just
happening at Radcliffe.

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:12.140
Everywhere we look
lately, we see

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:15.120
the language of gender
identity, the implications

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:17.850
of gendered language
for data analysis,

00:05:17.850 --> 00:05:21.270
and the role of gendered
language in public discourse.

00:05:21.270 --> 00:05:24.560
Let me share just a few
recent examples with you.

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:28.270
When David Bowie, a popular
music superstar over five

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:33.540
decades, died in January,
Salon.com ran a eulogy

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:37.650
with a headline that read "A
bold, knowing, charismatic

00:05:37.650 --> 00:05:40.640
creature neither
male nor female."

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:45.050
In the same month, Alicia
Garza, co-founder of Black Lives

00:05:45.050 --> 00:05:48.130
Matter movement criticized
President Barack Obama's State

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:50.720
of the Union for its
failure to address,

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:53.440
and these are
Garza's words, and I

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:56.960
quote, "the needs of black
cisgender and transgender women

00:05:56.960 --> 00:05:58.750
and black immigrant women."

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:01.750
Just yesterday, a headline
in the Harvard Crimson

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:05.700
that I noticed read "Gender
Neutral Bathroom Defaced."

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:09.250
Meanwhile, women's colleges
across the United States

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:11.910
are reassessing their
admissions policies

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:15.060
to take into account
transgender applicants.

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:18.210
Facebook, the popular
social media network,

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:23.820
now offers its users 50 gender
self-identification categories.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:26.970
And both the New York
Times and the Boston Globe

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:30.240
recently ran feature
articles on the search

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:34.760
for gender neutral pronouns
in the English language,

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.560
a search that turns out
to have been going on

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:39.580
for a very long time.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:43.110
Geoffrey Chaucer and Jane
Austen, just to mention two,

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:45.180
both racked their
literary brains

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:50.170
for gender neutral
alternatives to "he" and "she."

00:06:50.170 --> 00:06:53.210
In fact, the American
Dialect Society

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:56.320
has just named the
word "they," when

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:00.070
used as a gender neutral
singular pronoun,

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:03.910
as its Word of
the Year for 2015.

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:07.010
And I could go on, but I
think you get the point.

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.690
The relationship between
gender and language

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.660
is so ubiquitous that
it can become a bit

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:17.140
like the air, something that is
so constantly present that we

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:21.720
never really stop to notice it
because we rarely think about

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:25.020
it in any sustained
or purposeful way.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:30.340
So today, we will stop to focus
on the interplay between gender

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:34.240
and language at this
precise moment in time.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:38.320
Our aim today is more
descriptive than prescriptive.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:41.540
We strive to question
and to understand.

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:44.040
And to help us, we have
an impressive group

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:46.850
of panelists and
speakers, and John Huth

00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:49.970
will provide us with a fuller
overview to all of them

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:50.830
in just a moment.

