00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:52.280
So let me begin by
answering the question

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:53.780
that I've gotten
a number of times

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:55.113
with respect to this conference.

00:08:55.113 --> 00:08:59.040
How can an experimental
particle physicist

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:01.720
in the physics department
at Harvard University

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:03.710
host a conference
or how did I come

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:06.550
to host a conference
on language and gender?

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:09.230
Because it seems like
a bit of a stretch.

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:10.280
So let me explain.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:12.310
First of all, the
partial answer is

00:09:12.310 --> 00:09:15.540
Radcliffe really pushes
me a lot and it's

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:16.900
been a learning experience.

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:22.830
But there are two stories that
created this, in some sense.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:27.530
So the first was I was a
minority male in a majority

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:31.810
female meeting at Radcliffe and
I noticed the discourse, which

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:34.700
I couldn't really get into
because I couldn't figure out

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:35.344
the rules.

00:09:35.344 --> 00:09:36.510
And so somebody would speak.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:38.270
Somebody else, the
next person, would

00:09:38.270 --> 00:09:40.290
reflect what the
other person said

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:42.660
and then go into their thoughts.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:45.360
After that meeting, I went to
a physics department meeting,

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:46.920
which was majority male.

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:50.390
And the men would just
interrupt each other constantly

00:09:50.390 --> 00:09:52.560
and the few women
in the audience

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:55.365
couldn't get a word in edgewise.

00:09:55.365 --> 00:09:56.990
And there was no
reflection whatsoever.

00:09:56.990 --> 00:09:59.220
So that was very striking.

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:01.140
In fact, it was something
that I had learned

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:04.697
about as an abstract
concept in the 1970s,

00:10:04.697 --> 00:10:06.280
but I'd never really
thought about it.

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:08.940
And here I was presented
with a living realization

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:12.530
in two meetings of this
dynamic that I'd heard about.

00:10:12.530 --> 00:10:16.870
The other was a few months later
at my church, the United Parish

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:20.826
of Auburndale, we had a
transgender minister come

00:10:20.826 --> 00:10:22.200
and give a sermon,
but the sermon

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:25.460
was really about the
challenges that he

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:29.980
faced basically transitioning,
coming out, discrimination,

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:33.620
poverty, all sorts of issues.

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:37.540
And then we had a panel
of transgender people

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:40.040
who would talk about
their experiences

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:43.430
and just amplified
what the minister said.

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:46.040
But what emerged
in that discussion

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:48.970
was the importance of
language to these people.

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:51.040
I mean, for example,
just the pronouns

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:56.120
that are used for you
can either be helpful

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:59.480
or they can be almost an
attack on your person.

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:02.220
And these two things
coupled together

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:06.480
made me, for the next year,
hyper-alert to the language

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:11.090
of gender, and I was constantly
seeking out more information

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:14.040
and noticing that
things were in flux.

00:11:14.040 --> 00:11:17.450
In a lot of cases, I make
the mistaken assumption

00:11:17.450 --> 00:11:19.890
that when I enter a
culture or an institution,

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:21.920
that things are dynamic.

00:11:21.920 --> 00:11:24.790
But really, over time, I find
that things are changing.

00:11:24.790 --> 00:11:28.810
And so what I was
really seeing was

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:30.560
that there was some
segment of language

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:33.630
and the language of
gender that was changing.

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:37.040
Now, the study of language
and gender is not new.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:42.750
In fact, at least as far back
as 1665, it was written about.

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:45.730
There was a writer,
Charles de Rochefort,

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:49.770
who wrote about a language
in the Lesser Antilles

00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:53.680
where the people, if you
as an outsider just entered

00:11:53.680 --> 00:11:56.350
and listened to what was
going on, it seemed like women

00:11:56.350 --> 00:11:59.350
and men were speaking
entirely different languages.

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:01.560
This was 1665.

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:06.490
More recently, the studies
of gender and language

00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:10.010
emerged in the 1960s
where, for example, it

00:12:10.010 --> 00:12:14.240
was observed that women tend to
lead linguistic change rather

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:14.740
than men.

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:19.030
So if you really want to find
what's the rules of language,

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:22.390
you go to an elder
male in that society

00:12:22.390 --> 00:12:24.920
because they're the last
ones to change their language

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:27.520
habits, which it's true.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:30.880
Feminists such as
linguist Robin Lakoff

00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:34.970
studied this in the 70s, Penny
Eckert into the 80s, and so on.

00:12:34.970 --> 00:12:37.200
So the question is, what's new?

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:38.950
What can we learn now?

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:40.310
Because languages are in flux.

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:44.520
In fact, the flux, the
changes, the mutation rate,

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:48.620
is so predictable that if
you take a proto-language

00:12:48.620 --> 00:12:51.180
and then you take and
separate two groups of people

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:55.550
geographically, you can study
the languages after some length

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:58.440
of time and by knowing
the mutation rate,

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:02.420
you can identify how long
ago the languages separated

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:05.620
from the proto-language just by
understanding the change rate.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:07.800
Not only that,
but a language may

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.580
come in contact with
another language

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:12.140
and absorb some of the terms
from the other language

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:13.590
until it becomes commonplace.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:15.360
And so sometimes
there are arcs where

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:20.220
a word may be the neutral
word of the borrowed language,

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:22.056
may have a pejorative
connotation

00:13:22.056 --> 00:13:23.430
as it gets absorbed,
and then may

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.900
get grasped by the people
who it's describing.

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:31.300
So rather than to
examine language

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:33.674
as a purely academic
concept, what

00:13:33.674 --> 00:13:35.090
I wanted to do for
this conference

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:38.040
was to turn the tables
and use language

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:42.390
as a kind of lens or mirror with
which we can look at culture

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:45.400
and use the changes in
language as a way of examining

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:46.510
the changes in culture.

00:13:46.510 --> 00:13:48.540
So it's basically
turning the table

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:51.830
on what you might call a
language or a linguistic study.

00:13:51.830 --> 00:13:54.395
So to do that, we're
bringing together

00:13:54.395 --> 00:13:55.770
people who, I
would say, would be

00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:58.690
on the front lines
of linguistic change,

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:00.350
the practitioners,
the people who

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:04.040
are employing words themselves
in an everyday sense,

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.420
studying the changes
in an everyday sense.

00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:11.330
So using that theme, we arrived
at the panels and the speakers

00:14:11.330 --> 00:14:14.140
that we have before you today.

00:14:14.140 --> 00:14:15.170
And I'll work backwards.

00:14:15.170 --> 00:14:19.090
So the last part of the
day is public discourse,

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:22.150
where we have people who
are active in politics,

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:27.400
advertising, and in
screenwriting and directing.

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:31.880
And the idea there is
that ostensibly, at least

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:33.690
at a first blush,
you might imagine

00:14:33.690 --> 00:14:38.270
that the target audience
would be 50% men, 50% women.

00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:43.845
Yet the content that's being
generated is by 95% men.

00:14:43.845 --> 00:14:45.720
So you might ask the
question, to what extent

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:49.640
does that reinforce
all sorts of norms that

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:52.260
may not be obvious to people?

00:14:52.260 --> 00:14:56.610
And how do advertising
executives, screenwriters,

00:14:56.610 --> 00:15:02.210
for example, tackle
this when they're women?

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:05.510
Before that, we have
a session on big data.

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:09.760
The emergence of social
networking, social media

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:12.550
can provide both
a tool for people

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:15.490
to use to understand
language usage--

00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:18.440
what does that tell us, what
is the experience of people

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:22.290
online based on their gender,
and what kind of new language

00:15:22.290 --> 00:15:24.460
might emerge?

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:28.670
Last night, Robin Young
actually recapitulated a problem

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:32.550
that I had with the
term "LOL" in texting.

00:15:32.550 --> 00:15:35.150
Like me, she thought
it meant Lots of Love.

00:15:35.150 --> 00:15:39.220
And so it led to odd
texts like, "Boy, you're

00:15:39.220 --> 00:15:41.480
going up against a big
challenge this morning.

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:43.430
I wish the best for you.

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:44.040
Good luck.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:44.810
LOL."

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:48.340
And so I actually
committed that mistake

00:15:48.340 --> 00:15:50.710
myself, which is a good
example that you'd better

00:15:50.710 --> 00:15:53.620
know the usage of a term
before you start throwing it

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:55.052
out trying to be hip.

00:15:58.150 --> 00:16:03.720
And our morning session
is entitled Beyond Binary.

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:06.180
And we have Janet
Mock, who will be

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:09.540
speaking as a keynote
interviewed by Moya Bailey.

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:12.420
So what we're trying
to explore here

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:16.510
is how the emergence, to a
greater public awareness,

00:16:16.510 --> 00:16:21.660
of trans issues has created,
in some sense, a language

00:16:21.660 --> 00:16:24.080
challenge-- for example,
the usage of pronouns.

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:28.660
But even more than that, it's
a question that a lot of people

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:31.550
are not wanting to be
identified by a specific binary.

00:16:31.550 --> 00:16:33.760
So what we'll hear, I
think, about the concept

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:36.370
of passing and whether
or not that's even

00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:38.980
a good concept at all.

00:16:38.980 --> 00:16:42.540
I'll notice that
dictionaries, for example,

00:16:42.540 --> 00:16:45.980
capture what you might call
the old male sense of what

00:16:45.980 --> 00:16:49.420
words are viable in a language.

00:16:49.420 --> 00:16:53.700
So I'll note that the Oxford
English Dictionary in 2003

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:58.400
entered "transgender" as a
word and "cisgender" in 2013

00:16:58.400 --> 00:16:59.050
as a word.

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:02.970
So already, there is some
sense of change as captured

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:05.240
by the OED.

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:06.829
In terms of "they"
as a singular,

00:17:06.829 --> 00:17:09.849
it's also a generational marker.

00:17:09.849 --> 00:17:14.790
I note that my daughters
use it all the time.

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:18.250
When I talk with friends
of my generation,

00:17:18.250 --> 00:17:20.290
they will immediately
correct me.

00:17:20.290 --> 00:17:22.460
On the other hand,
I've slipped into this.

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:25.780
When I've been writing
in books and papers,

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:27.859
I sometimes use
"they" unconsciously.

00:17:27.859 --> 00:17:29.670
I didn't even realize
that I was doing it.

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:34.050
But in fact, I did use
"they" and I got corrected.

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:37.860
So we'll be exploring the
issue of gender binary

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:41.750
and the question of how people
would like to be identified

00:17:41.750 --> 00:17:45.310
and how language can be
used in a positive fashion.

00:17:45.310 --> 00:17:49.100
One woman last night was
talking about the desire

00:17:49.100 --> 00:17:53.650
to raise her child in
a gender neutral home

00:17:53.650 --> 00:17:57.040
and, more recently, in a
pangender home, so the sense

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:00.910
that the child can pick and
choose gender attributes

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:03.760
in this different way.

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:07.090
So what I'd like to do
is invite the panel up.

00:18:07.090 --> 00:18:13.700
So we have Rebecca
Bigler, Wesley Thomas,

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:15.250
and Bear Bergman.

00:18:15.250 --> 00:18:18.730
And to moderate the panel,
we have Stephanie Burt.

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:19.684
So can you come up?

00:18:19.684 --> 00:18:21.100
And while you're
taking the stage,

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:27.200
I'll just close with
one, I guess, anecdote.

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:31.280
Last night, thinking
about this panel,

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:35.640
I went into my Facebook page and
went to the little identifiers.

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:40.960
And I chose my gender
to be "cismale"

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:43.600
and I also chose my
pronoun to be "they."

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:46.060
So when my birthday
comes up in two weeks,

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:49.400
people are going to see, "John
Huth's birthday is today.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:51.320
Wish them a happy birthday."

00:18:51.320 --> 00:18:52.771
So-- [LAUGHTER]

00:18:52.771 --> 00:18:53.270
No.

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:54.380
You can go up and check.

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:55.980
OK.

00:18:55.980 --> 00:19:00.620
So you can see that
I'm in dynamic change.

00:19:00.620 --> 00:19:01.250
OK.

00:19:01.250 --> 00:19:03.440
So the moderator
for today's panel

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.501
is Stephanie Burt, who is
a professor of English.

00:19:06.501 --> 00:19:07.000
-Hi.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:07.499
Yeah.

00:19:07.499 --> 00:19:09.220
-And a poet--

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:09.910
-Yep.

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:12.660
---writes poetry, but
also writes about poetry.

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:17.130
And I just wanted to share
the title of one book that

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:21.960
stood out to me, which was Close
Calls with Nonsense-- Reading

00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:23.100
New Poetry.

00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:25.150
So I have to pick that up.

00:19:25.150 --> 00:19:26.260
So Stephanie?

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:27.460
-It's waiting for you.

00:19:27.460 --> 00:19:28.294
Thank you.

00:19:28.294 --> 00:19:31.752
