00:19:36.031 --> 00:19:36.530
OK.

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:37.890
Thank you all for coming.

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:40.370
I believe it's my job
to introduce and, what

00:19:40.370 --> 00:19:44.140
do we say, contextualize
our panelists who

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:48.120
we're so lucky to have
had travel to be here.

00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:51.180
And we will have
about 15 minutes

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:56.270
of each of our panelists
speaking, Rebecca Bigler

00:19:56.270 --> 00:19:58.472
and Wesley Thomas
and Bear Bergman.

00:19:58.472 --> 00:20:00.222
And are we going to
go in that order, or--

00:20:00.222 --> 00:20:00.722
-Yeah.

00:20:00.722 --> 00:20:01.360
-OK.

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:02.430
Great.

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:05.370
We'll then have
20 minutes of talk

00:20:05.370 --> 00:20:09.540
among ourselves, as it were, and
then 20 minutes or so of time

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:10.430
for your questions.

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:11.180
Is that right?

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:13.010
Yeah.

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:15.700
I have been asked to
introduce and contextualize.

00:20:15.700 --> 00:20:17.770
What's your pronoun?

00:20:17.770 --> 00:20:21.270
That question was
unusual, except maybe

00:20:21.270 --> 00:20:24.790
in an introductory language
class, 10 or 12 years ago.

00:20:24.790 --> 00:20:29.070
And now it's something
that a lot of us

00:20:29.070 --> 00:20:33.210
hear frequently or
regularly, especially

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:38.430
if we identify as trans
or are under a certain age

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:40.940
or are teachers.

00:20:40.940 --> 00:20:44.030
Notice "or" not "and."

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:45.667
Some of us even have two names.

00:20:45.667 --> 00:20:46.750
And thank you, by the way.

00:20:46.750 --> 00:20:48.160
I'm Stephanie today.

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:51.230
Both names and all
the pronouns you

00:20:51.230 --> 00:20:55.150
can think of that are
for people are correct.

00:20:55.150 --> 00:20:59.610
I'm going to continue to be
both, but I am Stephanie today.

00:20:59.610 --> 00:21:01.150
And that, again,
is something that I

00:21:01.150 --> 00:21:04.440
can say to this crowd of lots of
people-- thank you for coming--

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:05.840
and it will sort of make sense.

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:07.756
And you've probably heard
it from other people

00:21:07.756 --> 00:21:08.580
in other places.

00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:11.210
These are indications
that language is changing

00:21:11.210 --> 00:21:15.490
and society is changing,
and each kind of change

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:17.660
helps drive the other.

00:21:17.660 --> 00:21:22.060
And things are changing
not just for people

00:21:22.060 --> 00:21:24.800
with unusual
relationships to gender,

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:29.280
but for everyone, as
a result. And things

00:21:29.280 --> 00:21:34.270
are changing audibly and
legibly as well as visibly.

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:37.160
Things are changing
not only around

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:39.670
conversational and
informal language,

00:21:39.670 --> 00:21:42.940
but around legal
language, the language

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:46.570
that government
institutions use to regulate

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:48.700
or attempt not to regulate us.

00:21:48.700 --> 00:21:50.700
Things are changing
for works of art.

00:21:50.700 --> 00:21:53.380
Things are changing in
terms of what is possible

00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:56.040
and what has to be
explained and what

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:59.280
the baseline of assumptions
possible for a set of readers

00:21:59.280 --> 00:22:02.820
is for essayists and memoirists
like Bear Bergman, who

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:04.820
I'm so happy to have here.

00:22:04.820 --> 00:22:05.840
Hi.

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:10.370
Things are changing for
memoirists of many other kinds.

00:22:10.370 --> 00:22:12.730
Things are changing for poets.

00:22:12.730 --> 00:22:16.800
In 2013, Troubling the Line,
which is a terrific book

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:19.080
that you should check out
if you read modern poetry,

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:20.410
appeared from Nightboat Books.

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:23.280
It is the first, and it's
a very big, anthology

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:27.560
of trans and gender queer
poets and writings on poetry.

00:22:27.560 --> 00:22:29.150
And I'm sure there will be more.

00:22:29.150 --> 00:22:32.030
Things are changing
for comic books.

00:22:32.030 --> 00:22:36.960
One of my favorite current comic
books is Jem and the Holograms.

00:22:36.960 --> 00:22:39.770
If you saw the movie, I'm sorry.

00:22:39.770 --> 00:22:42.504
If you watched the TV show
growing up, good for you.

00:22:42.504 --> 00:22:44.420
Whether or not you did
either of those things,

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:46.530
you might want to check
out this comic, which

00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:50.270
is very interested in visual as
well as legible representations

00:22:50.270 --> 00:22:53.030
of different ways, in
particular, of being a woman

00:22:53.030 --> 00:22:54.580
and of being a girl.

00:22:54.580 --> 00:22:56.590
One of the artists,
the artist who

00:22:56.590 --> 00:22:59.580
has the most to do with a look
of the comic, Sophie Campbell,

00:22:59.580 --> 00:23:01.390
who is out as a translady.

00:23:01.390 --> 00:23:04.520
And in the current issue, number
12, of the current plot-line,

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:06.730
one of the supporting
characters comes out as trans.

00:23:06.730 --> 00:23:08.230
They're also doing
amazing things

00:23:08.230 --> 00:23:11.310
with other kind of
inclusive language

00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:13.410
and with girls' and
women's body shapes.

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:16.540
And we should do something
about comics here,

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:17.490
gender in the visual.

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:23.030
Maybe that's for 2018, but
one more partly verbal medium

00:23:23.030 --> 00:23:25.870
in which you can really
see language change just

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:27.500
over the past few years.

00:23:27.500 --> 00:23:30.650
And it's changing in
terms of the language

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:34.860
that we use with children
and about children

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:38.360
as well as the language we use
with our college age students,

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:41.940
or if we are college age--
traditional college age,

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:46.120
I should say-- or 30
or 40 or 50 or 85.

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:48.040
I have two awesome children.

00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:51.240
And when I meet people
and they discover

00:23:51.240 --> 00:23:54.480
that I have two awesome
children, I'm often asked,

00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:56.270
is each one a girl or a boy?

00:23:56.270 --> 00:23:58.320
And they're 5 and 10
and we're pretty sure.

00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:01.060
But when they were infants,
I was always tempted first

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:04.920
to say, why is that the first
question you're asking me;

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:07.460
I wish it were not,
and then to say,

00:24:07.460 --> 00:24:11.300
well, we think
that we have a boy,

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:14.410
but of course we won't know for
sure until they're two or three

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:16.270
and can tell us.

00:24:16.270 --> 00:24:21.950
I think that's actually the
right answer, of course.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:24.580
We'll know when they're or two
or three and they'll tell us.

00:24:24.580 --> 00:24:26.250
Probability suggests
that they're boys.

00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:29.130
And in fact, I have two boys.

00:24:29.130 --> 00:24:33.922
And why would that not
be the right answer?

00:24:33.922 --> 00:24:36.130
Why would you not say that
every time you were asked?

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:39.630
Why would that answer
make cisgender parents

00:24:39.630 --> 00:24:43.920
and non-parents
uncomfortable, if it does?

00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:46.890
Why is that still the first
question that parents get

00:24:46.890 --> 00:24:47.390
asked?

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:48.364
Why?

00:24:48.364 --> 00:24:49.340
Why?

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:54.220
I hope we'll get to answer
some of those questions today.

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:58.820
And I hope you see how
the answers are changing,

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:03.270
but how far we still have to go
and how many questions we still

00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:05.290
don't know the answers to.

00:25:05.290 --> 00:25:08.990
And I also hope today
that we are going to see,

00:25:08.990 --> 00:25:11.840
and this is some place where
audience participation can

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:15.230
really help, how not just what
social [INAUDIBLE] you use

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:17.120
and what year it is,
who your friends are,

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:19.600
and how old you
are affects the way

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:22.320
that language and gender
shape your sense of yourself

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:26.330
and of others, but also
how other actual languages

00:25:26.330 --> 00:25:28.970
can make the answers to
all those questions super

00:25:28.970 --> 00:25:30.090
different.

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:33.690
I don't read Persian,
although I do

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:36.830
read some poetry in
translation from Persian,

00:25:36.830 --> 00:25:38.480
and I know people
who read Persian.

00:25:38.480 --> 00:25:40.920
And it's my understanding
that pronouns in Persian

00:25:40.920 --> 00:25:42.670
do not have genders at all.

00:25:42.670 --> 00:25:45.260
Any Persian speakers?

00:25:45.260 --> 00:25:46.260
Yeah?

00:25:46.260 --> 00:25:46.960
Is that right?

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:47.745
-Yeah.

00:25:47.745 --> 00:25:48.370
-That is right?

00:25:48.370 --> 00:25:48.870
Thank you.

00:25:48.870 --> 00:25:51.030
OK.

00:25:51.030 --> 00:25:53.110
When I am speaking
English, I have

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:55.874
to tell people whether I prefer
"he" or "she" on a given day,

00:25:55.874 --> 00:25:57.540
and the answer is
usually both are fine.

00:25:57.540 --> 00:25:58.206
I'm "she" today.

00:25:58.206 --> 00:25:59.290
Hi.

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:01.100
But if we were all
speaking Persian,

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:04.500
this just wouldn't arise and we
could use that energy worrying

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:05.880
about something else.

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:07.510
I think that would
be really cool.

00:26:07.510 --> 00:26:09.110
I want to learn Persian.

00:26:09.110 --> 00:26:14.210
-Yeah, but then a lot of us
would be out of jobs, so--

00:26:14.210 --> 00:26:20.180
-Well, I feel like
you'd be fine.

00:26:20.180 --> 00:26:21.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:21.150 --> 00:26:26.560
Your range as a writer
extends far beyond that.

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:29.460
But that's just one example.

00:26:29.460 --> 00:26:30.960
My understanding
is that we're going

00:26:30.960 --> 00:26:32.880
to be hearing from
Wesley Thomas about some

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:36.690
of the ways in which different
kinds of gendered language

00:26:36.690 --> 00:26:40.470
happen in Navajo or Dine.

00:26:40.470 --> 00:26:41.950
Did I pronounce that correctly?

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:42.450
-Yes.

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:42.950
-Dine.

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:44.240
Yeah.

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:49.040
We will be hearing more
about gender and expectations

00:26:49.040 --> 00:26:53.020
and how children use
language from Rebecca Bigler.

