00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:00.720
-I'm Rebecca Bigler.

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:05.530
I'm delighted to be here
and open our session.

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:09.860
The title of my talk is Gendered
Language and Sexist Thought.

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:12.490
I want to just start by
briefly acknowledging

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:15.590
two important collaborators
in my life academics,

00:28:15.590 --> 00:28:18.280
Campbell Leaper at
UC-Santa Cruz and Lynn

00:28:18.280 --> 00:28:20.690
Liben at the Pennsylvania
State University.

00:28:20.690 --> 00:28:23.770
I take full responsibility
for my remarks today,

00:28:23.770 --> 00:28:26.910
but I want to acknowledge their
contributions to my thought

00:28:26.910 --> 00:28:28.880
and work.

00:28:28.880 --> 00:28:33.160
So hypotheses about the relation
between language on one hand

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:36.080
and thought on the other
date back centuries.

00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:39.770
Although many mysteries
remain, psychological science

00:28:39.770 --> 00:28:43.870
has discovered much about
how the two are connected.

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:46.050
The relation between
language and thought

00:28:46.050 --> 00:28:48.390
is reciprocally causal.

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:50.700
Each shapes the
other in ways that

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:53.370
are consequential
for human behavior.

00:28:53.370 --> 00:28:55.880
My primary interest
today is in the principle

00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:58.100
of linguistic
relativity often known

00:28:58.100 --> 00:29:02.080
as the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis,
which states that language

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:05.470
shapes the ways that
people perceive and think

00:29:05.470 --> 00:29:07.030
about the world.

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:11.060
Words refer to concepts and
having a word for something

00:29:11.060 --> 00:29:13.820
affects how one thinks
about the world.

00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:17.950
In my talk, I will summarize
new and striking evidence

00:29:17.950 --> 00:29:23.050
that the mere use of words
to denote or mark gender,

00:29:23.050 --> 00:29:24.950
referred to as
gendered language,

00:29:24.950 --> 00:29:27.420
facilitates gender bias.

00:29:27.420 --> 00:29:31.500
In other words, my thesis
will be that gendered language

00:29:31.500 --> 00:29:35.320
causes sexist thought.

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:38.050
Languages across the
world vary in the extent

00:29:38.050 --> 00:29:41.230
to which they mark gender and
the ways in which they do so.

00:29:41.230 --> 00:29:45.090
For the purposes of my talk, I
am going to focus on English.

00:29:45.090 --> 00:29:48.780
The English language includes
many means of marking gender,

00:29:48.780 --> 00:29:57.491
including honorific titles,
occupational titles, pronouns.

00:30:02.370 --> 00:30:05.690
Two points about gendered
language are important.

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:10.790
First, words that denote gender
in English use a binary system.

00:30:10.790 --> 00:30:13.210
There are two
dichotomist markings

00:30:13.210 --> 00:30:15.510
for gender, male and female.

00:30:15.510 --> 00:30:17.700
There is no
linguistic convention

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:19.720
in English for
marking individuals

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:24.650
who fall outside of or between
the categories male and female.

00:30:24.650 --> 00:30:28.840
Second, it is typically,
but not always, possible

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:32.130
to use gender neutral
nouns to label people

00:30:32.130 --> 00:30:34.090
and thus, speakers
and writers can

00:30:34.090 --> 00:30:38.680
opt or not to specify someone's
gender in a statement.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:40.440
There are obviously
some contexts

00:30:40.440 --> 00:30:42.830
in which it's pertinent
to mark individuals'

00:30:42.830 --> 00:30:44.560
gender, for example,
when discussing

00:30:44.560 --> 00:30:47.100
some medical conditions
that are sex linked

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:50.010
or discussing gender
discrimination.

00:30:50.010 --> 00:30:52.130
In the vast majority
of instances,

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:56.550
however, individuals' gender
is marked unnecessarily,

00:30:56.550 --> 00:30:59.080
as when teachers
greet their students,

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:00.950
"Good morning, boys
and girls" instead

00:31:00.950 --> 00:31:04.320
of "Good morning, students"
or a parent informs a spouse,

00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:06.380
"I'll pick up the
girls from school"

00:31:06.380 --> 00:31:09.260
rather than, "I'll pick
up the kids from school."

00:31:09.260 --> 00:31:13.160
Unlike nouns, however, English
singular third person pronouns

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:16.020
require the marking of gender.

00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:19.320
As a consequence, it is
nearly impossible in English

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:21.850
to write or talk about
other individuals

00:31:21.850 --> 00:31:26.230
without indicating their
gender and simultaneously

00:31:26.230 --> 00:31:29.770
forcing them into the
category male or female.

00:31:29.770 --> 00:31:32.660
So what, one might ask?

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:35.690
One possible response is
that gendered language

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:38.900
reifies a gender
binary view and thus

00:31:38.900 --> 00:31:41.400
does not allow for
individuals who

00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:45.100
have identities that fall
between or outside of male

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:46.030
or female.

00:31:46.030 --> 00:31:49.480
Indeed, some individuals have
identities outside the gender

00:31:49.480 --> 00:31:52.120
binary and this,
I would argue, is

00:31:52.120 --> 00:31:56.320
sufficient grounds for
calling for language reform.

00:31:56.320 --> 00:31:59.090
It is not, however,
the only basis

00:31:59.090 --> 00:32:00.930
to call for language reform.

00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:04.830
Although the routine use of
gender labeling via nouns

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:08.070
and pronouns has been a long
accepted practice in English

00:32:08.070 --> 00:32:10.840
in the United States,
there is mounting evidence

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:14.270
of harmful consequences
associated with the practice,

00:32:14.270 --> 00:32:16.490
especially among children.

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:20.340
Empirical evidence suggests that
rather than being innocuous,

00:32:20.340 --> 00:32:24.610
gendered language profoundly
affects children's gender

00:32:24.610 --> 00:32:27.130
stereotyping and prejudice.

00:32:27.130 --> 00:32:31.820
It does so via the
processes of categorization

00:32:31.820 --> 00:32:34.410
and conceptualization.

00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:36.960
It is now well established
that language affects

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:40.010
children's categorization
of both inanimate objects

00:32:40.010 --> 00:32:42.430
and animate beings.

00:32:42.430 --> 00:32:45.450
In the words of
Roger Brown, "Words

00:32:45.450 --> 00:32:50.320
serve as invitations to
form categories" and infants

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:54.830
and young children readily
accept such invitations.

00:32:54.830 --> 00:32:56.900
The clearest
demonstration of the power

00:32:56.900 --> 00:32:59.290
of labels to induce
categorization

00:32:59.290 --> 00:33:01.640
comes, perhaps, from
the systematic research

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:03.080
of Sandra Waxman.

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:04.900
Waxman and her
colleagues have shown

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:07.560
that infants between
three months of age

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:10.610
and two years of age
respond differently

00:33:10.610 --> 00:33:13.440
to the identical
stimuli as a function of

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:16.280
whether or not they
are given a noun label.

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:19.840
For example, Booth and Waxman
presented 14-month-old infants

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:24.260
with small models of familiar
stimuli such as cars or horses.

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:27.870
Some infants heard the objects
labeled with the same noun,

00:33:27.870 --> 00:33:30.290
whereas others were presented
with the same objects

00:33:30.290 --> 00:33:31.530
with no labels.

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:34.100
On test trials,
infants were more

00:33:34.100 --> 00:33:38.350
likely to select a familiar
than a novel category object

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:42.030
if they had been
exposed to labels only.

00:33:42.030 --> 00:33:45.060
In later work, the authors
extended the paradigm

00:33:45.060 --> 00:33:48.490
to novel stimuli,
eliminating the possibility

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:51.070
that the words were
merely calling to mind

00:33:51.070 --> 00:33:53.300
already formed categories.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:56.230
For example, infants who
heard novel objects labeled

00:33:56.230 --> 00:33:58.550
with the same noun were
more likely to respond

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:01.600
to the perceptual
commonalities among the objects

00:34:01.600 --> 00:34:05.420
than infants who
did not hear labels.

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:11.550
Categorization, in turn, affects
conceptualization of stimuli.

00:34:11.550 --> 00:34:14.850
Categorization leads
children to make inferences

00:34:14.850 --> 00:34:16.520
about category members.

00:34:16.520 --> 00:34:21.870
For example, categorization
induces essentialist reasoning.

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:25.219
Essentialist reasoning is
defined as the tendency

00:34:25.219 --> 00:34:30.219
to believe that category members
share natures or essences that

00:34:30.219 --> 00:34:32.360
make them what they are.

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:34.060
Susan Gelman and
her colleagues have

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:37.190
generated an impressive
array of evidence

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:39.510
that category
labels lead children

00:34:39.510 --> 00:34:42.699
to infer that the
members of a category

00:34:42.699 --> 00:34:47.420
share inherent, deep,
meaningful commonalities, even

00:34:47.420 --> 00:34:51.690
in the absence of perceptual
or conceptual similarities.

00:34:51.690 --> 00:34:54.080
Consistent with this
notion, preschool children

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:58.050
readily make gender
stereotypic inferences

00:34:58.050 --> 00:35:01.420
about unfamiliar children on
the basis of their gender noun

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:04.590
labels and gendered first names.

00:35:04.590 --> 00:35:08.110
Thus, children raised in the
presence of pervasive gender

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:11.250
noun labels are
likely to categorize

00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:16.180
others they encounter by gender
and assume that same gender

00:35:16.180 --> 00:35:18.520
individuals are
similar to each other

00:35:18.520 --> 00:35:22.280
in many and important ways.

00:35:22.280 --> 00:35:26.430
Given that essentialist thought
characterizes children's views

00:35:26.430 --> 00:35:29.770
of social categories, the
learning of gender categories

00:35:29.770 --> 00:35:32.030
is likely to promote
stereotyping.

00:35:32.030 --> 00:35:36.390
Indeed, categorization has long
been considered a key process

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:40.510
in the development of all
social stereotypes and biases.

00:35:40.510 --> 00:35:45.090
In 2006, Lynn Liben and I
published a theoretical account

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:48.310
of the formation of social
stereotypes and prejudices

00:35:48.310 --> 00:35:51.210
in children titled
"Developmental Intergroup

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:52.220
Theory."

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:56.660
We noted that humans vary
along myriad dimensions which

00:35:56.660 --> 00:36:00.550
offer children bases for
classification including

00:36:00.550 --> 00:36:05.270
height, hair color, handedness,
whether your earlobes are

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:09.180
attached or not,
gender, race, etc.

00:36:09.180 --> 00:36:12.460
We argued that
children look to cues

00:36:12.460 --> 00:36:16.140
from adults about which
attributes should serve

00:36:16.140 --> 00:36:18.320
as a basis for classification.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:22.010
Gendered language
is a powerful cue.

00:36:22.010 --> 00:36:24.590
It leads children to
categorize themselves

00:36:24.590 --> 00:36:26.650
and others on that basis.

00:36:26.650 --> 00:36:29.020
As a consequence of
such categorisation,

00:36:29.020 --> 00:36:33.050
children, as I noted, endorsed
gender essentialist views

00:36:33.050 --> 00:36:35.310
and attend to and
learn the attributes

00:36:35.310 --> 00:36:38.250
that are linked with gender
in their environment.

00:36:38.250 --> 00:36:41.790
As a result, children
as young as age three

00:36:41.790 --> 00:36:46.740
rigidly endorse stereotypes
about occupations, activities,

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:49.650
traits, and other attributes.

00:36:49.650 --> 00:36:51.390
In addition to
affecting children's

00:36:51.390 --> 00:36:54.080
gender-related cognitions,
gendered language

00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:57.030
appears to affect children's
affect, their interests,

00:36:57.030 --> 00:36:58.640
and their behavior.

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:01.170
As noted earlier, the
psychological salience

00:37:01.170 --> 00:37:03.570
of gender induced
by labels leads

00:37:03.570 --> 00:37:06.730
children to categorize
themselves into gender in-group

00:37:06.730 --> 00:37:10.660
and gender out-groups,
triggering strong preferences

00:37:10.660 --> 00:37:12.850
for same gender peers.

00:37:12.850 --> 00:37:16.370
For example, children who
have acquired an understanding

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:20.650
of the words "boy" and "girl"
spend more time playing

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:23.270
with same gender
peers than do children

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:25.480
without such knowledge.

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:28.450
Furthermore, experimental
manipulations

00:37:28.450 --> 00:37:31.480
of the degree to which gender
is labeled, for example,

00:37:31.480 --> 00:37:34.470
by preschool teachers
in a classroom

00:37:34.470 --> 00:37:38.840
shows causal effects on those
preschoolers' peer relations,

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:41.280
with children showing
declines in play

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:44.620
with cross-gender peers when
their preschool teachers label

00:37:44.620 --> 00:37:47.680
gender, as in, "Good
morning, boys and girls."

00:37:47.680 --> 00:37:51.080
Many additional studies
show that gendered labeling

00:37:51.080 --> 00:37:54.230
affects children and
adults' personal preferences

00:37:54.230 --> 00:37:55.900
and behavior.

00:37:55.900 --> 00:37:58.610
Finally, additional
evidence for the role

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:01.890
of category labeling in
producing stereotypes

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:05.960
and prejudice comes from
studies of novel categories.

00:38:05.960 --> 00:38:10.030
In my own long line of
25 years of research,

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:13.300
I place children in novel
social groups, often

00:38:13.300 --> 00:38:16.960
red and blue groups, and
manipulate the characteristics

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:21.230
of the environment over as
many as two months of school.

00:38:21.230 --> 00:38:25.190
What I find in our line
of work is that when

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:28.349
teachers label the novel groups
saying, "Good morning, reds

00:38:28.349 --> 00:38:30.390
and blues" and, "Blues,
line up" and, "Let's have

00:38:30.390 --> 00:38:33.210
a blue bulletin board and
a red bulletin board,"

00:38:33.210 --> 00:38:37.930
children become biased on the
basis of group membership.

00:38:37.930 --> 00:38:40.020
When, on the other
hand, teachers

00:38:40.020 --> 00:38:43.050
ignore those group differences,
even though they're

00:38:43.050 --> 00:38:45.570
highly perceptually
salient, children

00:38:45.570 --> 00:38:49.250
do not develop biases at all.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:51.610
To sum up, consistent
with the principle

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:54.320
of linguistic relativity,
gendered language

00:38:54.320 --> 00:38:56.520
has been shown to
influence individuals'

00:38:56.520 --> 00:39:00.030
gender-related cognitions,
affect, and behavior.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.590
Specifically, the use
of gendered language

00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:05.930
appears to cause children
to attend to gender,

00:39:05.930 --> 00:39:08.770
categorize themselves
and others by gender,

00:39:08.770 --> 00:39:11.120
and believe that the
members of gender

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:14.600
share deep, meaningful,
important similarities.

00:39:14.600 --> 00:39:16.940
In addition, the
use of gender labels

00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:21.360
leads children to construct and
learn stereotypes about gender

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:24.080
and show in-group favoritism.

00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:25.030
OK.

00:39:25.030 --> 00:39:27.960
Because the use
of gendered labels

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:33.690
appears to precipitate a
cascading sequence of gender

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:37.870
salience, categorization,
stereotyping, and prejudice,

00:39:37.870 --> 00:39:41.040
some individuals have
called for the elimination

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:43.890
of the routine and
non-purposeful use of gender

00:39:43.890 --> 00:39:44.720
labels.

00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:46.950
Teachers, for
example, could refrain

00:39:46.950 --> 00:39:48.750
from using gender
to label children

00:39:48.750 --> 00:39:50.760
and organize their classrooms.

00:39:50.760 --> 00:39:53.780
Imagine, for example, that a
teacher greeted his students

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:56.550
with the phrase, "Good
morning, blacks and Latinos.

00:39:56.550 --> 00:39:59.010
Let's have the white
children get their pencils.

00:39:59.010 --> 00:40:03.190
Could we sit white, Latino,
white, Latino today?"

00:40:03.190 --> 00:40:09.910
That, in fact, violates federal
law, and for good reason.

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:14.420
I would like to see similar
laws prohibit the use of gender

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:17.050
to routinely label
and organize children

00:40:17.050 --> 00:40:18.720
in educational settings.

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:21.434
I'm looking for a lawyer
who wants to do that.

00:40:21.434 --> 00:40:22.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:22.250 --> 00:40:24.780
Consistent with this
idea, US colleges

00:40:24.780 --> 00:40:28.260
have instituted policies, some
that minimize gender labeling

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:30.510
and classification,
including the creation

00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:33.860
of all-gender dorms and
all-gender bathrooms.

00:40:33.860 --> 00:40:38.090
Oberlin College, for example,
my alma mater, uses an E system.

00:40:38.090 --> 00:40:40.980
Bathrooms are marked with
a default E for Everyone,

00:40:40.980 --> 00:40:43.660
but that E can be
rotated to temporarily

00:40:43.660 --> 00:40:49.350
make it W for Women and
M for Men. [LAUGHTER]

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:54.520
This solution, like
others, including this one,

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:59.360
are insufficient in my view,
however, because they continue

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:02.060
to make gender
salient to children

00:41:02.060 --> 00:41:05.700
and use gender as a
basis for classification.

00:41:05.700 --> 00:41:09.418
My ideal marking of bathrooms
would be something like this.

00:41:09.418 --> 00:41:10.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:12.520
Although it is
possible for speakers

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:14.880
to avoid gendered
nouns, this is not

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:16.830
possible with English pronouns.

00:41:16.830 --> 00:41:18.930
The absence of gender
neutral pronouns

00:41:18.930 --> 00:41:22.550
is problematic for many reasons,
but among them is the work

00:41:22.550 --> 00:41:24.070
that I just described.

00:41:24.070 --> 00:41:27.760
Empirical evidence suggests that
gendered language causes sexist

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:28.470
thought.

00:41:28.470 --> 00:41:30.860
To address this problem,
an increasing number

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:32.520
of speakers and
writers are using

00:41:32.520 --> 00:41:37.230
new gender neutral pronouns
such as "ze" and "hir,"

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:40.300
just one of several
possible conventions.

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:43.920
Indeed, in the last year, I
have come to refer to myself

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:46.550
and request that
others refer to me

00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:49.190
using gender neutral pronouns.

00:41:49.190 --> 00:41:52.110
The request derives
from my conviction

00:41:52.110 --> 00:41:55.200
that altering linguistic
input to youth, including

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:57.660
the elimination of
routine gender labeling

00:41:57.660 --> 00:42:00.260
and the introduction of
gender neutral pronouns,

00:42:00.260 --> 00:42:03.200
is an essential
component of efforts

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:07.250
to prevent gender stereotyping
and prejudice in children.

00:42:07.250 --> 00:42:10.030
Indeed, I would argue
that it is a necessary,

00:42:10.030 --> 00:42:14.670
albeit not sufficient, component
of preventing and reducing

00:42:14.670 --> 00:42:16.730
stereotyping in children.

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:20.240
It is my hope and belief
that freeing children

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:23.720
from proscriptive and
prescriptive labels and beliefs

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:28.290
about gender will lead them to
lead happier, more fulfilling,

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:30.872
and more productive lives.

00:42:30.872 --> 00:42:31.372
Thank you.

00:42:31.372 --> 00:42:35.260
[APPLAUSE]

00:42:41.999 --> 00:42:42.790
-Thank you so much.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.510
We're going to hear from
everybody individually

00:42:45.510 --> 00:42:48.320
before we have an exchange.

00:42:48.320 --> 00:42:49.070
Wesley Thomas?

00:42:53.030 --> 00:42:55.060
-[SPEAKING NAVAJO]

00:43:02.630 --> 00:43:05.480
Good morning.

00:43:05.480 --> 00:43:11.770
When we greet and
address an audience,

00:43:11.770 --> 00:43:19.140
we generally go beyond who
is visually in our visions.

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:22.370
We greet to the
middle of the universe

00:43:22.370 --> 00:43:29.390
and to the middle of the
earth, to all points.

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:33.450
We sing greetings to all
living things in between when

00:43:33.450 --> 00:43:35.630
we use our language.

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:39.420
And our language is
considered powerful.

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:43.190
We construct our
reality with our words.

00:43:43.190 --> 00:43:48.860
So it's really shunned
on if you insult somebody

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:50.950
because you're
literally telling them

00:43:50.950 --> 00:43:56.330
where to go, for an example, and
there's repercussion to that.

00:43:56.330 --> 00:44:01.140
And so language and
words are very important.

00:44:01.140 --> 00:44:03.240
What you're saying
is what you really

00:44:03.240 --> 00:44:09.520
mean because you took the time
to conjure up that thought.

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:14.920
So thought and enacting it,
you present it in speech.

00:44:14.920 --> 00:44:16.780
And there, you
construct the reality

00:44:16.780 --> 00:44:19.400
of what's going to happen,
what's going to take place,

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:22.740
and how you greet
people outside of you.

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:30.750
One of the works that I've
been doing for quite a while,

00:44:30.750 --> 00:44:35.670
probably similar to
Rebecca, about 25, 30 years,

00:44:35.670 --> 00:44:38.220
one point when I got
into graduate school,

00:44:38.220 --> 00:44:40.490
I had to go back
to, I guess, called

00:44:40.490 --> 00:44:47.060
ground zero to look at the
evolution of our creation

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:48.930
stories.

00:44:48.930 --> 00:44:56.260
We have creation stories that
provide us the guidance of how

00:44:56.260 --> 00:44:58.070
to live your life.

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:01.700
So it all goes back
to the creation story.

00:45:01.700 --> 00:45:05.190
If there's a question, we always
go back to the creation story

00:45:05.190 --> 00:45:07.830
because that's the
ones that establish

00:45:07.830 --> 00:45:11.290
all the rules of how to live.

00:45:11.290 --> 00:45:19.020
In that, also, is
gender identity.

00:45:19.020 --> 00:45:22.860
How did gender evolve?

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:26.190
And I had to go back
to the creation story.

00:45:26.190 --> 00:45:30.570
And in that, I was
not a medicine person.

00:45:30.570 --> 00:45:33.455
Within the many tribes
through the United States,

00:45:33.455 --> 00:45:36.960
there are very few
and selected people

00:45:36.960 --> 00:45:39.440
who serve as medicine people
with their particular tribes.

00:45:39.440 --> 00:45:42.880
By the way, there's
about 557 tribes

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:46.730
in the United States recognized
by the federal government.

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:49.490
An additional 300-plus
is not recognized

00:45:49.490 --> 00:45:52.240
by the federal government
because they either

00:45:52.240 --> 00:45:57.290
had a very low number or
they lost their language.

00:45:57.290 --> 00:46:00.290
So language becoming
a very critical part

00:46:00.290 --> 00:46:02.530
in Native communities,
that you actually

00:46:02.530 --> 00:46:07.220
have to speak it to
not be eliminated

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:09.880
as a federal government
in the United States.

00:46:09.880 --> 00:46:15.180
So there's about 150 that
are in that gray area.

00:46:15.180 --> 00:46:20.060
Out of that 557, I would
estimate probably 120 of them

00:46:20.060 --> 00:46:23.662
still have access
to the language.

00:46:23.662 --> 00:46:27.300
Of those, that particular
group, about 25% of them

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:29.300
have direct connection
to the language,

00:46:29.300 --> 00:46:31.850
but not necessarily
speak it fluently.

00:46:31.850 --> 00:46:34.020
I'd say probably less
than 10 of the tribes

00:46:34.020 --> 00:46:36.690
in the United States are
fluent in the language

00:46:36.690 --> 00:46:39.880
and you still hear
that in their homes.

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:42.720
So it's a very, very
small percentage.

00:46:42.720 --> 00:46:49.650
So language plays a huge role
in maintaining their status

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:52.150
under the US government.

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:56.040
So in my work, I was
very curious about gender

00:46:56.040 --> 00:46:58.210
because when I was
about five years old,

00:46:58.210 --> 00:47:01.160
my father-- we'd go to one
of the winter ceremonies.

00:47:01.160 --> 00:47:04.290
And these men and women are
dancing outside in the winter

00:47:04.290 --> 00:47:05.489
and it's snowing.

00:47:05.489 --> 00:47:07.780
And he said, you need to
watch that because, as I said,

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:11.420
when you grow up, you have to
dance in that particular dance

00:47:11.420 --> 00:47:12.810
that they're doing.

00:47:12.810 --> 00:47:15.900
And I was very
curious as to, why me?

00:47:15.900 --> 00:47:17.140
What about my cousins?

00:47:17.140 --> 00:47:19.360
What about my neighbors?

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:21.620
How come they can't do that?

00:47:21.620 --> 00:47:26.180
And he basically told me
'cause you're born into it.

00:47:26.180 --> 00:47:30.750
That is part of your individual
heritage, that you do that.

00:47:30.750 --> 00:47:36.000
And in those dances,
there's obviously,

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.693
men dancing, males dancing.

00:47:41.430 --> 00:47:43.560
There's a representation
of female.

00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:45.150
And these were not females.

00:47:45.150 --> 00:47:50.930
These were men dressed
in women's clothing,

00:47:50.930 --> 00:47:53.100
and very feminine.

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:56.624
And I just had a
passing and seeing that

00:47:56.624 --> 00:47:58.040
and then I've never
really thought

00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:03.290
about it until later
on why is they're

00:48:03.290 --> 00:48:06.060
representing the women in it?

00:48:06.060 --> 00:48:12.100
And in my own studies, I was
looking at religion worldwide

00:48:12.100 --> 00:48:16.829
and I've noticed that most
of them are male dominated.

00:48:16.829 --> 00:48:17.870
Just look at the Vatican.

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:25.290
In our own tribe, women cannot
be part of the ceremonies

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:33.440
because women have natural
power which supersedes man-made

00:48:33.440 --> 00:48:36.930
ceremonies, man-made religion.

00:48:36.930 --> 00:48:39.902
Women have natural powers
through their menstruation.

00:48:39.902 --> 00:48:41.360
So in a lot of
writings, they would

00:48:41.360 --> 00:48:44.640
say that women are isolated
or that it's considered bad

00:48:44.640 --> 00:48:47.620
or-- women were isolated
in tribal communities

00:48:47.620 --> 00:48:50.410
because of the natural
power they possess.

00:48:50.410 --> 00:48:53.010
They would undo ceremonies.

00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:55.160
So there was a big
separation there.

00:48:55.160 --> 00:49:02.600
And in that are what are
called now the third gender,

00:49:02.600 --> 00:49:10.220
are people who are born as
male, but switched or clearly

00:49:10.220 --> 00:49:16.600
define their feminine
side and evolve and live

00:49:16.600 --> 00:49:21.220
the life of girls and
emerge into womanhood

00:49:21.220 --> 00:49:23.810
and live their lives as women.

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:25.650
So these are the ones
I call third gender.

00:49:25.650 --> 00:49:29.970
And we also have female
children, female babies,

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:33.010
who function in the
role of boys and men.

00:49:33.010 --> 00:49:34.695
Those are the fourth gender.

00:49:34.695 --> 00:49:37.630
I had to create distinctly
those four to make

00:49:37.630 --> 00:49:39.990
sense of what was going on.

00:49:39.990 --> 00:49:45.270
And this is all from a
traditional Navajo perspective.

00:49:45.270 --> 00:49:48.820
This is something that
is obviously there

00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:50.440
through their eyes.

00:49:50.440 --> 00:49:53.970
And we're not even entertaining
a Western construct.

00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:59.210
And that's coming
later in my work.

00:49:59.210 --> 00:50:04.830
In this, I was looking at,
why do traditional people view

00:50:04.830 --> 00:50:07.650
this as a third gender?

00:50:07.650 --> 00:50:11.130
And my work also began looking
at some of the works being done

00:50:11.130 --> 00:50:13.636
by anthropologists,
sociologists,

00:50:13.636 --> 00:50:17.940
about the continuum of culture.

00:50:17.940 --> 00:50:20.140
My grandmother, my
great-grandmother,

00:50:20.140 --> 00:50:22.150
all of those
people, are-- today,

00:50:22.150 --> 00:50:26.600
I would consider them
traditional people.

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:31.240
My mother, she has access
to all of modern technology.

00:50:31.240 --> 00:50:35.000
She understands English,
but doesn't speak it.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.660
And so I'd classify her
as being a transitional.

00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:40.440
She is in the transition
in having access

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:44.020
to a lot of things from
the Western culture.

00:50:44.020 --> 00:50:47.310
And I can't fit into
those two categories.

00:50:47.310 --> 00:50:53.480
Because traditionals don't
leave the reservation.

00:50:53.480 --> 00:50:55.130
They're monolingual.

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:58.750
They're completely rooted into
the traditional ceremonies.

00:50:58.750 --> 00:51:01.740
And the transitionals are
a little bit flexible,

00:51:01.740 --> 00:51:03.980
meaning they can
leave the reservation

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:06.480
and feel comfortable
outside for a while,

00:51:06.480 --> 00:51:09.090
but they're quite
insistent in the afternoon,

00:51:09.090 --> 00:51:10.730
they need to return
to the reservation.

00:51:10.730 --> 00:51:12.000
They need to go home.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:16.830
They're really reluctant to
spend a night away from home

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:18.516
because home is essential.

00:51:18.516 --> 00:51:19.140
It's important.

00:51:19.140 --> 00:51:20.950
Everything there is important.

00:51:20.950 --> 00:51:23.310
I'm in a contemporary category.

00:51:23.310 --> 00:51:25.490
That's the third one.

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:27.700
My Western education yanked
me into that category.

00:51:30.798 --> 00:51:34.010
And being bilingual
in the language

00:51:34.010 --> 00:51:37.830
and bicultural, live in
both of them, one at a time,

00:51:37.830 --> 00:51:40.270
not at the same time,
I think that creates

00:51:40.270 --> 00:51:43.190
a lot of confusion where you
try to live both of them.

00:51:43.190 --> 00:51:45.820
And then the fourth
category I've come up with

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:47.157
is-- I call them acculturated.

00:51:47.157 --> 00:51:48.990
They're in the process
of being acculturated

00:51:48.990 --> 00:51:50.260
into mainstream America.

00:51:50.260 --> 00:51:53.160
And then the last one, the
fifth one, assimilated.

00:51:53.160 --> 00:51:54.930
They've completely assimilated.

00:51:54.930 --> 00:51:57.395
This is just one particular
tribe, that's my tribe.

00:51:57.395 --> 00:52:03.230
The Navajo name is a name
given to us by the Spaniards.

00:52:03.230 --> 00:52:06.730
We don't mostly call ourselves--
if you really ask somebody

00:52:06.730 --> 00:52:09.660
on the reservation what tribe
are you, they would say Dine.

00:52:12.606 --> 00:52:16.280
I'm Dine-- I'm of the people.

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:20.500
"Navajo" is a colonial term.

00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:23.880
Then we generally don't go and
say oh, I'm American Indian

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:27.070
or I'm Native American
or Indigenous.

00:52:27.070 --> 00:52:29.170
Those are just lumping
people together.

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:37.041
In this identity issue,
some of my students--

00:52:37.041 --> 00:52:38.790
when I was teaching
at Indiana University,

00:52:38.790 --> 00:52:40.890
it was a really a good
example of my students.

00:52:40.890 --> 00:52:43.390
They would say, are
you American Indian?

00:52:43.390 --> 00:52:49.270
I would say yes because that
means there's less to explain.

00:52:49.270 --> 00:52:52.058
If I say I'm Dine, they
have no concept with it.

00:52:52.058 --> 00:52:56.900
Then I have to go into this long
spiel of explaining to them.

00:52:56.900 --> 00:52:59.290
So you have to pick and choose.

00:52:59.290 --> 00:53:03.670
So in a way, I think that's
called a situational identity.

00:53:03.670 --> 00:53:06.050
We have that one
[? quite ?] there.

00:53:09.530 --> 00:53:13.000
In that continuum, one
gender I focused on

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:14.950
was the third gender.

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:19.590
In Navajo, that's called
Natlee, N-A-T-L-E-E.

00:53:19.590 --> 00:53:23.810
If you look at that up there,
besides, you see "self."

00:53:23.810 --> 00:53:26.100
To the left of it,
it says "Natlee."

00:53:26.100 --> 00:53:30.920
There's a high tone marker
over the A. That's Natlee.

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:33.560
It basically means, in
Navajo language or Dine

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:38.630
language, that one who's in
a constant state of change.

00:53:38.630 --> 00:53:40.489
You don't know when
the change began.

00:53:40.489 --> 00:53:42.030
You don't know when
it's going to end

00:53:42.030 --> 00:53:43.505
or is it ever going to end.

00:53:43.505 --> 00:53:45.930
It's in that constant
state of change.

00:53:45.930 --> 00:53:47.010
That's the third gender.

00:53:50.600 --> 00:53:57.725
And this particular talk is from
one of the more recent writings

00:53:57.725 --> 00:53:58.350
that I'm doing.

00:53:58.350 --> 00:54:01.610
It's called "Development
and Evolution of Dine Third

00:54:01.610 --> 00:54:05.670
Gender," information from that.

00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:12.990
I was looking at we now have the
more modernized third gender.

00:54:12.990 --> 00:54:18.090
The Natlee was the
traditional third gender,

00:54:18.090 --> 00:54:25.530
but the TGs, transgenders, are
reinventing themselves, are

00:54:25.530 --> 00:54:28.140
rehashing some of
the terminologies

00:54:28.140 --> 00:54:32.970
that we had in the language
and beginning to use that.

00:54:32.970 --> 00:54:34.590
That's one of the
same reasons why

00:54:34.590 --> 00:54:39.400
on a broader scale in North
America and South America,

00:54:39.400 --> 00:54:43.400
we're going to need to use to
utilize the term two-spirit.

00:54:43.400 --> 00:54:49.310
Two-spirit is-- how
did that get created?

00:54:49.310 --> 00:54:55.290
In the '50s,
there's a major push

00:54:55.290 --> 00:54:59.690
to put Native
childrens in school.

00:54:59.690 --> 00:55:03.660
So they were taken to
boarding schools, some of them

00:55:03.660 --> 00:55:06.010
literally kidnapped from
whatever they were doing

00:55:06.010 --> 00:55:08.730
and put in boarding schools.

00:55:08.730 --> 00:55:10.710
Then there are those
who are voluntarily

00:55:10.710 --> 00:55:15.280
leaving the reservation in the
1960s because of the mandate

00:55:15.280 --> 00:55:18.540
that all children need to be
in schools and some of them

00:55:18.540 --> 00:55:22.050
didn't want to or some of them
prefer not to be in school.

00:55:22.050 --> 00:55:28.130
So people who would have
lived a life of Natlee

00:55:28.130 --> 00:55:31.220
within my reservation--
and each of the tribes

00:55:31.220 --> 00:55:34.140
in the United States
have their own term

00:55:34.140 --> 00:55:36.700
for third and fourth gender.

00:55:36.700 --> 00:55:39.440
There's some more work that
was done by Will Roscoe

00:55:39.440 --> 00:55:41.337
in collecting terminology.

00:55:44.570 --> 00:55:46.710
Like, for example,
the tribe south of us

00:55:46.710 --> 00:55:52.331
is the Zuni Pueblo, the third
gender there is called Lhamana.

00:55:52.331 --> 00:55:58.150
There's some major writings done
by Will Roscoe which is called

00:55:58.150 --> 00:56:04.824
We'wha came to Washington,
DC and went to the ball there

00:56:04.824 --> 00:56:10.020
and assumed she was a real woman
until later on, they found out.

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:12.280
And she did some
exhibition there.

00:56:12.280 --> 00:56:16.450
And she fell into the
third gender category.

00:56:16.450 --> 00:56:26.120
Because gender supersedes
your sexual identity.

00:56:26.120 --> 00:56:29.060
What you do as a
man or a woman is

00:56:29.060 --> 00:56:33.840
more important than
your biological makeup.

00:56:33.840 --> 00:56:37.890
Because your mind
and your spirit,

00:56:37.890 --> 00:56:40.350
the mental aspect
of you, is more

00:56:40.350 --> 00:56:45.290
important than biologically
of what you're made of

00:56:45.290 --> 00:56:48.610
and traditional
categories, that they

00:56:48.610 --> 00:56:53.450
see-- if you are
comfortable as a girl,

00:56:53.450 --> 00:56:56.850
there was permission
within tribes, especially

00:56:56.850 --> 00:57:02.290
tribes that were matrilineal,
that the women were

00:57:02.290 --> 00:57:05.970
the heads of household, that
the whole tribe was operating

00:57:05.970 --> 00:57:09.620
under the women's
rules, then patrilineal.

00:57:09.620 --> 00:57:11.860
Patrilineal, there was
a lot of confrontation.

00:57:11.860 --> 00:57:14.720
So there's very few
third and fourth gender

00:57:14.720 --> 00:57:17.580
in the patrilineal
tribal societies.

00:57:17.580 --> 00:57:20.520
These were warring
tribes of the past.

00:57:25.610 --> 00:57:28.430
I was just in San
Francisco two weeks ago.

00:57:28.430 --> 00:57:33.490
They had a big gathering of--
it's called the International

00:57:33.490 --> 00:57:36.060
Two-Spirit Powwow.

00:57:36.060 --> 00:57:38.790
So it's a lot of
dancing, powwow dancing,

00:57:38.790 --> 00:57:41.720
cross dressing powwows.

00:57:41.720 --> 00:57:46.070
There was Miss
International Two-Spirit,

00:57:46.070 --> 00:57:47.903
who was from
Shoshone-Bannock of Idaho.

00:57:47.903 --> 00:57:52.350
And I think the ceremony
takes place in Canada.

00:57:52.350 --> 00:57:54.316
I'm not sure where.

00:57:54.316 --> 00:57:55.630
But people like that.

00:57:55.630 --> 00:58:00.560
That was really fascinating to
see people in transition who

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:05.420
are just having their bodies
changed, breast removals, that

00:58:05.420 --> 00:58:13.260
were seen as men with
what do you call those?

00:58:13.260 --> 00:58:17.880
[NON-ENGLISH] It'll come to me.

00:58:17.880 --> 00:58:19.510
The English word
will come pretty soon

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:21.651
so we'll wait for it.

00:58:21.651 --> 00:58:22.593
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:23.984 --> 00:58:26.400
That's one of the other things
that's really a huge issue,

00:58:26.400 --> 00:58:28.660
is this whole
translation thing, trying

00:58:28.660 --> 00:58:32.070
to explain things while
thinking in Navajo

00:58:32.070 --> 00:58:35.420
and speaking in English.

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:39.080
And a lot of things
that we do now,

00:58:39.080 --> 00:58:41.670
we really depend on writing.

00:58:41.670 --> 00:58:45.370
Because I was looking at
our language to see why

00:58:45.370 --> 00:58:49.630
are this present generation
not speaking the language?

00:58:49.630 --> 00:58:52.310
Why are Native people
living on the reservation,

00:58:52.310 --> 00:58:56.790
hearing the language and having
direct access to the language,

00:58:56.790 --> 00:58:58.870
but not speak it?

00:58:58.870 --> 00:59:01.460
So I took a handful of students
and made them my Guinea pigs

00:59:01.460 --> 00:59:05.020
for a whole semester and just
talked to them, one on one

00:59:05.020 --> 00:59:09.400
and as a group, with
no text, no writing.

00:59:09.400 --> 00:59:14.250
The major problem was
they could not remember.

00:59:14.250 --> 00:59:18.190
Their memorization skills
have completely escaped.

00:59:18.190 --> 00:59:22.400
And I think that's really been
harmed by that with writing,

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:24.720
because every time
we hear something,

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:26.620
we don't let it go up.

00:59:26.620 --> 00:59:29.690
We let it come through
our hands and take a note.

00:59:29.690 --> 00:59:32.840
And we become
dependent on writing.

00:59:32.840 --> 00:59:35.470
It's a crutch for us.

00:59:35.470 --> 00:59:38.690
That's why we don't
remember things.

00:59:38.690 --> 00:59:42.002
If you have a conversation
with your grandmother

00:59:42.002 --> 00:59:43.460
or great-grandmother,
they remember

00:59:43.460 --> 00:59:46.130
things and dates and
times when things

00:59:46.130 --> 00:59:49.440
happen because they had
their memory skills,

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:53.960
and not necessarily
today's people.

00:59:53.960 --> 00:59:59.460
So there's really a lot
more to look into and talk

00:59:59.460 --> 01:00:02.090
about Navajo third gender.

01:00:02.090 --> 01:00:07.500
And this is not even dabbling
with current terminology

01:00:07.500 --> 01:00:09.020
of gay/lesbian.

01:00:09.020 --> 01:00:10.700
Those are Western identity.

01:00:10.700 --> 01:00:13.830
Those are not traditional
Native identities.

01:00:13.830 --> 01:00:16.560
We don't necessarily
identify with that.

01:00:16.560 --> 01:00:19.740
So for an example, when
I'm on the reservation

01:00:19.740 --> 01:00:23.550
and dancing the wintertime
in women's clothing,

01:00:23.550 --> 01:00:25.320
I'm considered Natlee.

01:00:25.320 --> 01:00:27.890
And then when I'm in
Native communities,

01:00:27.890 --> 01:00:29.710
I'm considered two-spirit.

01:00:29.710 --> 01:00:31.690
I don't identify myself as that.

01:00:31.690 --> 01:00:34.000
People have labeled
me with that.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:37.270
And then when I'm off the
reservation, flying here,

01:00:37.270 --> 01:00:42.010
being in Boston, I'd
probably label as being gay.

01:00:42.010 --> 01:00:48.180
So that's your perception of
who I am, and it's not who I am.

01:00:48.180 --> 01:00:49.470
So it just depends.

01:00:49.470 --> 01:00:59.294
I have to react to
my location and make

01:00:59.294 --> 01:01:00.710
it a little
comfortable for people

01:01:00.710 --> 01:01:02.090
around me and for myself.

01:01:02.090 --> 01:01:04.770
And then when I change
audience, like when

01:01:04.770 --> 01:01:06.480
I go back to the
reservation, then it's

01:01:06.480 --> 01:01:07.940
a totally different one.

01:01:07.940 --> 01:01:08.900
-Thank you.

01:01:08.900 --> 01:01:09.650
I hope we'll get--

01:01:09.650 --> 01:01:10.220
-[INAUDIBLE].

01:01:10.220 --> 01:01:12.180
-There's so much more I
hope we can get back to

01:01:12.180 --> 01:01:13.450
during the question period.

01:01:13.450 --> 01:01:16.830
I want to be sure that all three
of our speakers have the time

01:01:16.830 --> 01:01:18.090
that we need.

01:01:18.090 --> 01:01:18.590
Bear?

01:01:18.590 --> 01:01:20.458
-I was at that powwow, too.

01:01:20.458 --> 01:01:21.392
That's so funny.

01:01:21.392 --> 01:01:22.793
I was just there two weeks ago.

01:01:22.793 --> 01:01:24.670
-Mm-hmm.

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:25.490
-Good morning.

01:01:25.490 --> 01:01:26.430
-Good morning.

01:01:26.430 --> 01:01:27.190
-Oh, I love that.

01:01:27.190 --> 01:01:28.510
Thank you very much.

01:01:28.510 --> 01:01:30.750
Really, I'm a storyteller
and not an academic.

01:01:30.750 --> 01:01:33.170
And when I say "good morning"
at academic conferences

01:01:33.170 --> 01:01:36.480
and everyone looks
at me like, I always

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:37.646
feel a little uncomfortable.

01:01:40.890 --> 01:01:43.200
I'm so excited about
everything that I've already

01:01:43.200 --> 01:01:45.950
heard that I just really want to
spend my time talking about all

01:01:45.950 --> 01:01:49.310
of it, but I'm going to do the
other thing instead and get

01:01:49.310 --> 01:01:51.210
to that later.

01:01:51.210 --> 01:01:55.800
In the fall of 1993, I
got into my first argument

01:01:55.800 --> 01:01:58.680
with a university professor
about the validity

01:01:58.680 --> 01:02:01.640
of gender nonspecific pronouns.

01:02:01.640 --> 01:02:04.280
It was the first
of what would prove

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:08.810
to be many such arguments
in the fullness of time.

01:02:08.810 --> 01:02:14.280
Freshly emboldened by the smarty
pantses with whom I spent hour

01:02:14.280 --> 01:02:18.170
upon hour chatting on
the proto internet,

01:02:18.170 --> 01:02:22.070
I explained to my professor
that, in actual fact,

01:02:22.070 --> 01:02:25.890
there was nothing
grammatically incorrect at all

01:02:25.890 --> 01:02:28.890
about the use of
these tiny words.

01:02:28.890 --> 01:02:32.820
I smugly recited
stanzas of Chaucer

01:02:32.820 --> 01:02:36.840
to prove the pedigree
of the word "hir"

01:02:36.840 --> 01:02:41.040
and then I held my head up and
praised the activists of Usenet

01:02:41.040 --> 01:02:44.510
who had invented the
word "ze" to go with it.

01:02:44.510 --> 01:02:47.720
Finally, I offered up
my cloth-bound Rutledge

01:02:47.720 --> 01:02:52.235
imprinted copy of Gender
Outlaw by Kate Bornstein,

01:02:52.235 --> 01:02:56.670
[APPLAUSE] sprinkled with
gender nonspecific pronouns

01:02:56.670 --> 01:03:00.140
that I hoped to validate
by their obviously

01:03:00.140 --> 01:03:06.400
serious serif type, and my
identity right along with them.

01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:10.270
My professor, a second
wave lesbian feminist

01:03:10.270 --> 01:03:14.410
in linen separates,
shook her head slowly.

01:03:14.410 --> 01:03:16.034
You know who I mean, right?

01:03:16.034 --> 01:03:20.350
[LAUGHTER] Those
are not words, she

01:03:20.350 --> 01:03:25.500
said and, wrinkling her
nose in evident distaste,

01:03:25.500 --> 01:03:28.390
followed her pronouncement
with another one,

01:03:28.390 --> 01:03:30.840
and that is not a woman.

01:03:33.350 --> 01:03:36.180
Two things struck
me in the exchange

01:03:36.180 --> 01:03:39.620
and they continued to
reverberate for decades.

01:03:39.620 --> 01:03:43.590
One, that this professor
arrogated to herself the right

01:03:43.590 --> 01:03:46.450
to decide whether a
word was real or not.

01:03:46.450 --> 01:03:49.540
And two, that she
obviously felt this power

01:03:49.540 --> 01:03:54.330
extended to my gender identity
and that of many other people.

01:03:54.330 --> 01:03:57.840
The rejection of the word
stood in for the rejection

01:03:57.840 --> 01:04:01.400
of the concept, and
me in particular.

01:04:01.400 --> 01:04:05.770
Now, while I enjoy a little bit
of dictionary fetishism as much

01:04:05.770 --> 01:04:10.670
as the next writer, her
pronouncement and the judgment

01:04:10.670 --> 01:04:15.650
it contained were obviously
not about the words themselves,

01:04:15.650 --> 01:04:18.530
but about her disapproval
of the idea and, indeed,

01:04:18.530 --> 01:04:21.540
the people they described,
underlined by her choice

01:04:21.540 --> 01:04:27.820
to disdain both the words with
which Bornstein made it clear

01:04:27.820 --> 01:04:32.500
that "ze" did not consider
herself a woman and also hir

01:04:32.500 --> 01:04:36.370
[? gendered ?]
[? presentation-- ?] grandly

01:04:36.370 --> 01:04:39.880
Goth-infused, high femme
situation we've all come

01:04:39.880 --> 01:04:41.770
to love.

01:04:41.770 --> 01:04:46.770
People who experience themselves
as neither men nor women

01:04:46.770 --> 01:04:51.500
or some combination thereof?

01:04:51.500 --> 01:04:53.670
Absolutely not, she said.

01:04:53.670 --> 01:04:56.680
And she put her sensible
Dansko clog down

01:04:56.680 --> 01:05:00.020
firmly on the subject.

01:05:00.020 --> 01:05:02.530
22 years later, the
Oxford English Dictionary

01:05:02.530 --> 01:05:05.860
announced that it had included
gender nonspecific pronouns

01:05:05.860 --> 01:05:08.660
and honorifics, including
the singular "they"

01:05:08.660 --> 01:05:09.900
to their volumes.

01:05:09.900 --> 01:05:13.770
And when I finished happy
dancing around the kitchen,

01:05:13.770 --> 01:05:16.110
I indulged at
length in a fantasy

01:05:16.110 --> 01:05:19.110
in which I could buy,
carefully highlight, and then

01:05:19.110 --> 01:05:23.540
mail several hundred volumes
to university professors

01:05:23.540 --> 01:05:26.540
around the world, marking the
page with an engraved card

01:05:26.540 --> 01:05:32.050
reading only "neener,
neener, neener." [LAUGHTER]

01:05:32.050 --> 01:05:36.350
For two decades, I campaigned
on behalf of the words "ze"

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:40.400
and "hir" with varying
degrees of success.

01:05:40.400 --> 01:05:42.580
I used them as my
personal pronouns

01:05:42.580 --> 01:05:45.070
and I insisted that
people use them

01:05:45.070 --> 01:05:49.290
for me in professional contexts,
which meant negotiating that

01:05:49.290 --> 01:05:55.020
whoever introduced my talk had
to read them out loud in front

01:05:55.020 --> 01:05:58.820
of other people and then I
had to listen to the speaker

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:02.730
make a tremendous performance
about how uncomfortable

01:06:02.730 --> 01:06:05.600
those words were
in their mouths.

01:06:05.600 --> 01:06:08.850
I pressed newspaper and
periodical writers and editors

01:06:08.850 --> 01:06:14.140
to use them in articles about
me with even less success.

01:06:14.140 --> 01:06:18.640
I wrote entire books using
gender nonspecific pronouns.

01:06:18.640 --> 01:06:21.370
And after going ten
rounds with my publisher

01:06:21.370 --> 01:06:24.250
that yes, they really
were real words

01:06:24.250 --> 01:06:27.430
and I really did have
the right to use them,

01:06:27.430 --> 01:06:30.450
fully half the reviews
my books received

01:06:30.450 --> 01:06:34.550
acknowledged that I
preferred "invented" pronouns

01:06:34.550 --> 01:06:37.360
or "neologisms"
and then proceeded

01:06:37.360 --> 01:06:41.520
to ignore them and use either
a masculine or feminine pronoun

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:42.560
set for me.

01:06:42.560 --> 01:06:46.130
I was never able to determine
how they chose which.

01:06:46.130 --> 01:06:50.910
I think someone in a back
office was just flipping a coin.

01:06:50.910 --> 01:06:54.470
Their choice was recently
unpleasantly echoed

01:06:54.470 --> 01:06:57.150
in a stunningly
dismissive New York Times

01:06:57.150 --> 01:07:01.430
article about Sasha Fleischman
of Oakland, California,

01:07:01.430 --> 01:07:03.560
a genderqueer
identified teenager

01:07:03.560 --> 01:07:08.900
who was set on fire
while riding a city bus.

01:07:08.900 --> 01:07:12.080
Evidently not content to
let the physical violence

01:07:12.080 --> 01:07:14.940
stand on its own, the
Gray Lady perpetrated

01:07:14.940 --> 01:07:20.800
its own linguistic violence with
the following parenthetical.

01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:24.900
"Telling Sasha's story also
poses a linguistic challenge

01:07:24.900 --> 01:07:27.340
because English doesn't
offer a ready-made way

01:07:27.340 --> 01:07:29.290
to talk about
people who identify

01:07:29.290 --> 01:07:31.290
as neither male or female.

01:07:31.290 --> 01:07:36.890
Sasha prefers 'they,' 'it,'
or the invented gender neutral

01:07:36.890 --> 01:07:41.190
pronouns 'ze.' The New York
Times does not use these terms

01:07:41.190 --> 01:07:42.990
to refer to individuals."

01:07:42.990 --> 01:07:44.560
-Yet.

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:46.170
-Let that sink in.

01:07:46.170 --> 01:07:47.070
-Yeah.

01:07:47.070 --> 01:07:47.570
Yeah.

01:07:47.570 --> 01:07:49.840
-In her book
Epistemic Injustice,

01:07:49.840 --> 01:07:52.500
British philosopher
Miranda Fricker

01:07:52.500 --> 01:07:55.630
describes two particular
kinds of oppression related

01:07:55.630 --> 01:07:57.960
to knowledge and language.

01:07:57.960 --> 01:08:02.970
One, she terms "testimonial
injustice," which she describes

01:08:02.970 --> 01:08:05.850
as the occasion
upon which prejudice

01:08:05.850 --> 01:08:08.770
causes a person to
be perceived as less

01:08:08.770 --> 01:08:13.480
credible or non-credible in
their capacity as an informant.

01:08:13.480 --> 01:08:16.250
The other is
"hermeneutical injustice,"

01:08:16.250 --> 01:08:20.710
where a person has no way
to describe their experience

01:08:20.710 --> 01:08:23.000
because the conceptual
frame doesn't yet

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:27.300
exist due to their stigmatized
or disempowered identity.

01:08:27.300 --> 01:08:29.830
And when I read her
book, I actually

01:08:29.830 --> 01:08:32.960
yelped in recognition
of the experience

01:08:32.960 --> 01:08:36.120
so robustly described.

01:08:36.120 --> 01:08:38.410
And making matters
worse, by the way,

01:08:38.410 --> 01:08:42.300
it's not just the suspender
professors and copyeditors

01:08:42.300 --> 01:08:46.189
of the world who have fought
me on every instance of gender

01:08:46.189 --> 01:08:48.060
nonspecific pronouns.

01:08:48.060 --> 01:08:50.930
There are plenty of
transgender identified

01:08:50.930 --> 01:08:53.910
people who rail
against the non-binary

01:08:53.910 --> 01:08:56.200
with just as much vigor.

01:08:56.200 --> 01:09:00.200
Their conviction, frequently
offered at some volume,

01:09:00.200 --> 01:09:03.490
is that the idea of
non-binary gender

01:09:03.490 --> 01:09:07.540
cheapens and distracts
from their experience,

01:09:07.540 --> 01:09:11.180
that it's all right to move
from the known and identified

01:09:11.180 --> 01:09:15.450
category of man to the known
and identified category of woman

01:09:15.450 --> 01:09:20.740
or vice versa, but not to say
that the categories are flawed,

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:23.779
optional, or even discussable.

01:09:23.779 --> 01:09:26.290
Though these people may
have trans identities

01:09:26.290 --> 01:09:30.370
or trans medical histories,
their relationship to gender

01:09:30.370 --> 01:09:33.020
is heteronormative and binary.

01:09:33.020 --> 01:09:37.790
There are two choices,
world without end, amen.

01:09:37.790 --> 01:09:40.720
And this too, I would argue,
is a matter of language

01:09:40.720 --> 01:09:42.880
as much as it is
of anything else.

01:09:42.880 --> 01:09:45.580
In Fricker's
parlance, trans people

01:09:45.580 --> 01:09:49.550
suffer a hermeneutical
injustice and non-binary people

01:09:49.550 --> 01:09:51.310
suffer it doubly.

01:09:51.310 --> 01:09:54.180
The cultural
imagination about anyone

01:09:54.180 --> 01:09:59.470
who is not normatively gendered,
trans bodies, identities,

01:09:59.470 --> 01:10:04.050
relationships, sex, geography,
conflict, priorities,

01:10:04.050 --> 01:10:08.620
is substantially influenced
by what we can write and talk

01:10:08.620 --> 01:10:10.580
about intelligibly.

01:10:10.580 --> 01:10:13.760
Since the modern conversation
about gender identity

01:10:13.760 --> 01:10:19.060
is so heavily medicalized, with
brief and chilling digressions

01:10:19.060 --> 01:10:21.830
into legal
terminology, so too are

01:10:21.830 --> 01:10:25.190
most of the words that
we have for ourselves

01:10:25.190 --> 01:10:28.650
and each other,
medical or legal legacy

01:10:28.650 --> 01:10:32.770
words designed to
reinforce the normal

01:10:32.770 --> 01:10:37.670
and shine the cold light
of inquiry on the other.

01:10:37.670 --> 01:10:42.060
We have no playful language,
no admiring language,

01:10:42.060 --> 01:10:45.740
no nuanced language, and
no affirming language.

01:10:45.740 --> 01:10:49.700
Instead, we're stuck with
obviously false dichotomies

01:10:49.700 --> 01:10:54.650
like "pre-op" and "post-op,"
which have led the entirety

01:10:54.650 --> 01:10:57.900
of cisgender humanity
into the beliefs that A,

01:10:57.900 --> 01:11:02.230
all transgender experience
is defined in relationship

01:11:02.230 --> 01:11:06.300
to surgical procedures that
have existed for about 75 years,

01:11:06.300 --> 01:11:09.340
even though trans people have
existed for millennia and I can

01:11:09.340 --> 01:11:14.660
prove that, and B, that there's
some sort of single opportunity

01:11:14.660 --> 01:11:19.340
trans medical intervention
somewhat akin to the television

01:11:19.340 --> 01:11:25.050
show Pimp My Ride where we
enter looking one way and emerge

01:11:25.050 --> 01:11:28.900
entirely different and perhaps
with some things chromed.

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:30.780
[LAUGHTER]

01:11:32.010 --> 01:11:35.230
What's more, the
process of moving away

01:11:35.230 --> 01:11:37.300
from medicalized
language, which is

01:11:37.300 --> 01:11:40.670
full of terrible
assumptions and worse ideas,

01:11:40.670 --> 01:11:44.860
but has the virtue of being
somewhat familiar even

01:11:44.860 --> 01:11:47.860
to people who are
distant from the topic,

01:11:47.860 --> 01:11:50.330
is messy and contested.

01:11:50.330 --> 01:11:54.110
There is no trans equivalent
of the Academie francaise

01:11:54.110 --> 01:11:56.480
where a group of
people meet, discuss,

01:11:56.480 --> 01:11:59.440
and decide which new
words are actually words

01:11:59.440 --> 01:12:02.280
and what they might mean.

01:12:02.280 --> 01:12:05.830
This leads to internal
conflict and heated debate

01:12:05.830 --> 01:12:08.540
among trans and
non-binary people

01:12:08.540 --> 01:12:10.540
about what words
are best to use.

01:12:10.540 --> 01:12:15.450
And because those debates
are entirely decentralized,

01:12:15.450 --> 01:12:19.390
unless you count
Tumblr, you could well

01:12:19.390 --> 01:12:22.460
find yourself using a word
that you learned in Chicago

01:12:22.460 --> 01:12:25.490
as respectful only to be
told in Atlanta that you're

01:12:25.490 --> 01:12:28.620
using oppressive
language and get out.

01:12:28.620 --> 01:12:33.480
As an educator, I spend a
lot of time explaining this,

01:12:33.480 --> 01:12:36.610
that trans communities
have just now come

01:12:36.610 --> 01:12:41.640
to a place where we have the
cultural agency, finally,

01:12:41.640 --> 01:12:46.270
to explain and describe
our own experience using

01:12:46.270 --> 01:12:48.790
our own language,
and that while this

01:12:48.790 --> 01:12:52.170
is a messy and
inconsistent process,

01:12:52.170 --> 01:12:56.630
it's also a pivotal,
and frankly thrilling,

01:12:56.630 --> 01:12:59.910
moment in identity development.

01:12:59.910 --> 01:13:03.580
I have some sympathy for
well-meaning non-trans people

01:13:03.580 --> 01:13:05.940
who desperately want
to get the lingo

01:13:05.940 --> 01:13:11.090
right as an act of ally-ship,
but it's too important

01:13:11.090 --> 01:13:13.430
and too exciting to rush.

01:13:13.430 --> 01:13:16.560
If we're going to eventually
be able to describe

01:13:16.560 --> 01:13:22.080
the specific, delicious,
nuanced particulars

01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:27.860
of our non-normative bodies
and experiences and identities,

01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:29.520
it's going to take some time.

01:13:32.030 --> 01:13:36.760
This is true even though the
larger cultural imagination,

01:13:36.760 --> 01:13:42.940
with its limited and limiting
understanding of trans

01:13:42.940 --> 01:13:45.770
and non-binary
experiences, can't

01:13:45.770 --> 01:13:49.110
fathom what we might be
taking our time about

01:13:49.110 --> 01:13:52.040
or why it could be so important.

01:13:52.040 --> 01:13:54.580
Most people, especially
the able-bodied,

01:13:54.580 --> 01:13:58.160
have rarely or never
had the experience

01:13:58.160 --> 01:14:01.720
of having a bodily
experience for which they

01:14:01.720 --> 01:14:08.090
have no word or no word
that they can stand to use.

01:14:08.090 --> 01:14:10.270
The frequent
exception to this rule

01:14:10.270 --> 01:14:13.170
turns out to be masturbation.

01:14:13.170 --> 01:14:16.380
The mental blank spot first
gets filled with a placeholder,

01:14:16.380 --> 01:14:19.830
like "this" or "that,"
and then maybe it

01:14:19.830 --> 01:14:25.390
evolves to a shorthand
codeword akin to a private joke

01:14:25.390 --> 01:14:30.840
with oneself or like the kind
of idiolects that married people

01:14:30.840 --> 01:14:33.880
inevitably develop over time.

01:14:33.880 --> 01:14:36.010
But eventually,
sometimes the moment

01:14:36.010 --> 01:14:41.340
arrives in which we hear
a word for the very thing

01:14:41.340 --> 01:14:44.990
and we see ourselves
reflected in it.

01:14:44.990 --> 01:14:47.190
As a non-binary
identified person,

01:14:47.190 --> 01:14:51.290
this was also my experience of
gender nonspecific pronouns.

01:14:51.290 --> 01:14:55.970
The jolt of understanding,
the dawning clarity

01:14:55.970 --> 01:15:00.180
of why I had shifted with
discomfort when people

01:15:00.180 --> 01:15:05.160
used feminine pronouns about
me, but had no special desire

01:15:05.160 --> 01:15:10.230
to run into the warm embrace
of masculine language,

01:15:10.230 --> 01:15:14.490
all but reset my
skeleton in my skin.

01:15:14.490 --> 01:15:17.830
Certainly, it shuffled
the deck of my locution

01:15:17.830 --> 01:15:21.120
and dealt me a hand I had
never previously understood

01:15:21.120 --> 01:15:23.880
to be a winner.

01:15:23.880 --> 01:15:27.040
Where non-binary
identities are concerned,

01:15:27.040 --> 01:15:29.180
the hermeneutical
injustice that applied

01:15:29.180 --> 01:15:32.010
to transpeople 20-odd
years ago still

01:15:32.010 --> 01:15:34.260
rages even though
trans identities

01:15:34.260 --> 01:15:36.070
have seen some progress.

01:15:36.070 --> 01:15:40.450
For non-binary identified or,
to use my current favorite term,

01:15:40.450 --> 01:15:43.710
NB people, this is
magnified by the fact

01:15:43.710 --> 01:15:46.420
that while most of
everyone, except Germaine

01:15:46.420 --> 01:15:49.860
Greer and Donald Trump,
are prepared to recognize

01:15:49.860 --> 01:15:53.640
that transpeople do
indeed exist these days,

01:15:53.640 --> 01:15:56.130
the NB population is
still struggling up

01:15:56.130 --> 01:15:58.240
the hill with our
glitter in one hand

01:15:58.240 --> 01:16:01.240
and our neckties in the other.

01:16:01.240 --> 01:16:03.530
These days, I deploy
the word "NB,"

01:16:03.530 --> 01:16:09.350
which is just a pronunciation of
the initials NB for non-binary,

01:16:09.350 --> 01:16:11.530
with casual authority.

01:16:11.530 --> 01:16:15.420
I neither explain nor
describe it unless asked.

01:16:15.420 --> 01:16:18.840
My part in the evolution of
language around NB topics

01:16:18.840 --> 01:16:21.170
and identities is
that I no longer

01:16:21.170 --> 01:16:24.480
engage in the kind of debates I
used to about whether something

01:16:24.480 --> 01:16:26.400
is or is not a word.

01:16:26.400 --> 01:16:28.040
I know better now.

01:16:28.040 --> 01:16:29.940
Of course it's a
word, I tell them,

01:16:29.940 --> 01:16:32.910
just like "laser" and
"radar" are words,

01:16:32.910 --> 01:16:36.710
just like we used to fax
things and now we Google them.

01:16:36.710 --> 01:16:39.596
I try not to even
mansplain about it.

01:16:39.596 --> 01:16:41.500
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:41.500 --> 01:16:44.090
But I'm wise to the
tactic now, this thing

01:16:44.090 --> 01:16:48.540
of pretending to have some
kind of high-minded linguistic

01:16:48.540 --> 01:16:52.640
objection to a new concept or
idea being expressed in order

01:16:52.640 --> 01:16:54.580
to conceal a prejudice.

01:16:54.580 --> 01:16:57.800
I've experienced enough
epistemic injustice

01:16:57.800 --> 01:17:00.250
to name it and
stand up for myself

01:17:00.250 --> 01:17:03.240
and people like me as
a legitimate expert

01:17:03.240 --> 01:17:05.160
in my own identity.

01:17:05.160 --> 01:17:07.630
With the cultural power
I have concentrated

01:17:07.630 --> 01:17:10.510
as a public intellectual,
a cultural worker,

01:17:10.510 --> 01:17:14.390
and let us not forget,
now, a white guy, I

01:17:14.390 --> 01:17:17.380
have become stalwart
in my assertions

01:17:17.380 --> 01:17:20.420
that people are and
can be trusted to be,

01:17:20.420 --> 01:17:23.290
in the words of educator
J. Wallace Skelton,

01:17:23.290 --> 01:17:25.740
experts on themselves.

01:17:25.740 --> 01:17:28.670
The smokescreen of being
challenged about words

01:17:28.670 --> 01:17:30.140
has given way.

01:17:30.140 --> 01:17:32.680
And it develops that people
are much more hesitant

01:17:32.680 --> 01:17:36.580
about saying, I think your
identity is invalid because it

01:17:36.580 --> 01:17:39.390
challenges my beliefs
about the world

01:17:39.390 --> 01:17:44.840
than they ever were about
saying, that's not a real word.

01:17:44.840 --> 01:17:47.162
Go figure.

01:17:47.162 --> 01:17:48.370
I just need two more minutes.

01:17:48.370 --> 01:17:48.870
-Yeah.

01:17:48.870 --> 01:17:52.080
-This becomes especially
clear when an NB person uses

01:17:52.080 --> 01:17:55.270
the singular "they"
pronoun and suddenly, there

01:17:55.270 --> 01:17:57.880
emerge strenuous
objections to it

01:17:57.880 --> 01:18:00.910
from people who consistently
misuse "lie" for "lay"

01:18:00.910 --> 01:18:04.350
and whose entire previous
commitment to grammar

01:18:04.350 --> 01:18:06.730
expired sometime around
the end of sentence

01:18:06.730 --> 01:18:09.750
diagramming in grade 10.

01:18:09.750 --> 01:18:11.580
It would be funnier
if it weren't

01:18:11.580 --> 01:18:15.590
so exhausting and demoralizing.

01:18:15.590 --> 01:18:19.880
In the 22 years between when
I started agitating on behalf

01:18:19.880 --> 01:18:23.350
of gender nonspecific pronouns
and when the OED joined

01:18:23.350 --> 01:18:26.540
the English language already
in progress about gender

01:18:26.540 --> 01:18:30.430
nonspecific pronouns, anointing
them, along with the gender

01:18:30.430 --> 01:18:33.820
nonspecific honorific
"Mx" and the word

01:18:33.820 --> 01:18:37.980
"cisgender," there has certainly
been some progress in language.

01:18:37.980 --> 01:18:42.230
The cisgender imagination,
especially that of gatekeepers

01:18:42.230 --> 01:18:46.470
of law, medicine, and language
whose imprimatur so many

01:18:46.470 --> 01:18:50.070
things have previously
required, is expanding,

01:18:50.070 --> 01:18:52.610
and with it must
go the language.

01:18:52.610 --> 01:18:56.660
Even the word "cisgender,"
a word created and deployed

01:18:56.660 --> 01:18:59.440
by trans and NB
people, now takes

01:18:59.440 --> 01:19:03.890
a fairly unchallenged place in
academia, at least, though it

01:19:03.890 --> 01:19:06.510
apparently upsets a
certain subset of people

01:19:06.510 --> 01:19:09.940
whose gender privilege is
so entrenched that they fuss

01:19:09.940 --> 01:19:12.330
and kick at being
named with a word

01:19:12.330 --> 01:19:16.620
that they didn't coin or
choose, to whom I say, welcome.

01:19:16.620 --> 01:19:18.000
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:19.840
-Yeah.

01:19:19.840 --> 01:19:24.700
-I begin to wonder, at this
point, what will happen next.

01:19:24.700 --> 01:19:26.920
Will the reality
of our lives become

01:19:26.920 --> 01:19:31.530
so present and incontrovertible
on the landscape of gender

01:19:31.530 --> 01:19:34.470
that refusal to use
our words will become

01:19:34.470 --> 01:19:37.190
the last refuge of the bigot?

01:19:37.190 --> 01:19:40.460
Will there be a backlash
against identity politics

01:19:40.460 --> 01:19:43.150
that causes cis people
to insist that they don't

01:19:43.150 --> 01:19:46.280
see gender and
therefore have no need

01:19:46.280 --> 01:19:48.700
to grapple with it anymore?

01:19:48.700 --> 01:19:54.410
How will we form systems, forms,
data, and codexes of language

01:19:54.410 --> 01:19:57.460
to capture the nuances
of gender identity,

01:19:57.460 --> 01:19:59.860
and what new points
of linguistic friction

01:19:59.860 --> 01:20:03.900
will each of those solutions
inevitably produce?

01:20:03.900 --> 01:20:08.750
Even for cisgender folks,
this is an exciting time.

01:20:08.750 --> 01:20:10.930
My friend Scott
Turner Schofield who

01:20:10.930 --> 01:20:14.490
used to be a performance artist
and is now a soap opera actor,

01:20:14.490 --> 01:20:19.380
which he claims is a lateral
move if ever there was one,

01:20:19.380 --> 01:20:22.840
tells a story I
have long enjoyed--

01:20:22.840 --> 01:20:24.470
I got it-- tells
a story I've long

01:20:24.470 --> 01:20:27.680
enjoyed about needing a
particular tool while traveling

01:20:27.680 --> 01:20:28.970
in Costa Rica.

01:20:28.970 --> 01:20:31.500
He had no idea what it
was called in Spanish

01:20:31.500 --> 01:20:33.650
and so he went to the
hardware store intending

01:20:33.650 --> 01:20:37.710
to browse the available items
and choose the thing he needed.

01:20:37.710 --> 01:20:39.260
But when he arrived,
he discovered

01:20:39.260 --> 01:20:42.280
that the store was more or
less a kiosk and all the tools

01:20:42.280 --> 01:20:45.170
were kept in the back
so a shopper was forced

01:20:45.170 --> 01:20:47.560
to ask for the thing
they wanted and wait

01:20:47.560 --> 01:20:49.350
for it to be fetched back.

01:20:49.350 --> 01:20:51.950
Scott, stumped by
this turn of events,

01:20:51.950 --> 01:20:54.654
produced in his limited
Spanish the following request

01:20:54.654 --> 01:20:55.445
[SPEAKING SPANISH].

01:21:00.770 --> 01:21:05.470
"I need the tool with the head
that's shaped like a church."

01:21:05.470 --> 01:21:08.240
After some puzzlement,
the clerk laughed

01:21:08.240 --> 01:21:10.930
and nodded and came back
with what he needed,

01:21:10.930 --> 01:21:13.890
a Phillips head screwdriver.

01:21:13.890 --> 01:21:16.650
This is exactly,
in so many ways,

01:21:16.650 --> 01:21:18.510
where we find the
language of trans

01:21:18.510 --> 01:21:20.760
and non-binary identities.

01:21:20.760 --> 01:21:24.730
Without knowing a word for
what we need, we approximate

01:21:24.730 --> 01:21:27.640
based on what we think
a conversation partner,

01:21:27.640 --> 01:21:31.910
reader, lover, doctor,
or government official

01:21:31.910 --> 01:21:34.150
might be familiar
with while we stand

01:21:34.150 --> 01:21:37.330
and wait wearing our most
cheerful and polite smiles

01:21:37.330 --> 01:21:40.440
and hope that the person will
find themselves willing to do

01:21:40.440 --> 01:21:43.500
the extra work to understand.

01:21:43.500 --> 01:21:45.400
In the hopeful future,
maybe the words

01:21:45.400 --> 01:21:48.910
of nuanced
descriptive and tender

01:21:48.910 --> 01:21:53.060
gendered language will be real
in our mouths and on our pages.

01:21:53.060 --> 01:21:57.080
But for now, we have to rely
on good will and creativity

01:21:57.080 --> 01:21:59.030
to get the job done.

01:21:59.030 --> 01:22:02.580
The good news is many of
us have a lot of both.

01:22:02.580 --> 01:22:03.410
Thank you.

01:22:03.410 --> 01:22:06.875
[APPLAUSE]

01:22:12.120 --> 01:22:13.230
-Thank you so much.

01:22:13.230 --> 01:22:14.230
Thank you for listening.

01:22:14.230 --> 01:22:16.780
Thank you to all three
of our panelists.

01:22:16.780 --> 01:22:20.490
And I think we're going
to go to maybe 12 or 13,

01:22:20.490 --> 01:22:23.550
instead of 15,
minutes for our talk

01:22:23.550 --> 01:22:26.455
because I know a lot of you
have a lot of questions.

01:22:29.420 --> 01:22:31.260
There we go.

01:22:31.260 --> 01:22:34.830
For my first question, I
wanted to hear Rebecca talk

01:22:34.830 --> 01:22:35.790
about this.

01:22:35.790 --> 01:22:36.820
And I had two questions.

01:22:36.820 --> 01:22:38.710
You can answer one
or both, I guess.

01:22:38.710 --> 01:22:46.000
So the first is obviously, this
audience and other audiences

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:48.800
within linguistics
and social linguistics

01:22:48.800 --> 01:22:51.700
seems to have been hospitable
to your discoveries and those

01:22:51.700 --> 01:22:55.460
that you cite, but how do
preschool teachers react?

01:22:55.460 --> 01:22:57.920
Have you gone to the
National Association

01:22:57.920 --> 01:22:59.970
for Early Childhood
Education, also known

01:22:59.970 --> 01:23:02.510
as NAECTE-- if you have
preschool age children,

01:23:02.510 --> 01:23:06.080
you may have heard of
it-- or other groups that

01:23:06.080 --> 01:23:09.060
actually train teachers of
young children and said,

01:23:09.060 --> 01:23:12.200
here's what you do, here's
what you've got to stop doing?

01:23:12.200 --> 01:23:13.990
And how has that been?

01:23:13.990 --> 01:23:17.040
And the other question
is, what's the endgame?

01:23:17.040 --> 01:23:20.270
In a just world, in the
world that you want to see,

01:23:20.270 --> 01:23:23.890
would you expect, based on
your own and others' research,

01:23:23.890 --> 01:23:29.070
groups of 5-year-olds,
8-year-olds, 12-year-olds who

01:23:29.070 --> 01:23:35.080
simply ignore the history
of self-identification that

01:23:35.080 --> 01:23:37.640
has some relation to
biological difference?

01:23:37.640 --> 01:23:41.050
Or would you expect gender
to be present in their play

01:23:41.050 --> 01:23:43.150
and their language,
but differently?

01:23:43.150 --> 01:23:45.400
What's the end game?

01:23:45.400 --> 01:23:46.050
-Yeah.

01:23:46.050 --> 01:23:47.110
Wonderful questions.

01:23:47.110 --> 01:23:52.410
And I do, indeed, do outreach
to teachers, the lay public.

01:23:52.410 --> 01:23:55.220
It's a huge part of
my identity and what

01:23:55.220 --> 01:23:59.610
I think academics have
an obligation to do.

01:23:59.610 --> 01:24:01.830
What I usually find
is that teachers

01:24:01.830 --> 01:24:06.400
are very surprised that their
language affects children.

01:24:06.400 --> 01:24:10.184
So they mostly say, for
example, well, yes, I say,

01:24:10.184 --> 01:24:12.350
"Good morning, boys or
girls" and "What a cute girl"

01:24:12.350 --> 01:24:14.160
or "Let's sit boy,
girl, boy girl."

01:24:14.160 --> 01:24:16.550
But I don't do it
to be sexist and I'm

01:24:16.550 --> 01:24:20.280
pretty sure I'm not making
children endorse gender

01:24:20.280 --> 01:24:21.970
stereotypes when I do that.

01:24:21.970 --> 01:24:24.550
They're just not aware of the
link between their language

01:24:24.550 --> 01:24:26.720
and children's responses.

01:24:26.720 --> 01:24:31.090
And I will just briefly say my
worst moment was with an older

01:24:31.090 --> 01:24:33.080
teacher, many years
of experience,

01:24:33.080 --> 01:24:36.280
who every morning, she had the
children count how many girls

01:24:36.280 --> 01:24:38.080
were present and put
up girl paper dolls

01:24:38.080 --> 01:24:40.500
and count how many boys were
present and put up a boy.

01:24:40.500 --> 01:24:43.450
And I said that that
would contribute

01:24:43.450 --> 01:24:47.020
to stereotyping in the
classroom and boys saying,

01:24:47.020 --> 01:24:49.260
we're better than
girls and girls--

01:24:49.260 --> 01:24:51.800
and she said well, God
made them boys and girls

01:24:51.800 --> 01:24:53.900
and I'm going to
label them that way

01:24:53.900 --> 01:24:56.150
if I want to, to
which I said, yeah,

01:24:56.150 --> 01:24:57.700
well, God made them
black and white

01:24:57.700 --> 01:25:01.610
and you don't label that label
in that way, do you, which

01:25:01.610 --> 01:25:06.070
led to me being just ostracized
and it was a terrible moment

01:25:06.070 --> 01:25:08.140
with the school.

01:25:08.140 --> 01:25:10.680
But I do find them
receptive to education.

01:25:10.680 --> 01:25:13.190
And particularly, pointing
out the parallels to race

01:25:13.190 --> 01:25:16.520
has been affective
about routine labeling.

01:25:16.520 --> 01:25:19.020
Now, I want to get
to the end game

01:25:19.020 --> 01:25:20.660
because I don't
think the answer is

01:25:20.660 --> 01:25:22.910
to become what we have
done often with race,

01:25:22.910 --> 01:25:25.750
to be race blind or
to be gender blind.

01:25:25.750 --> 01:25:28.080
That is, I'm not arguing
that we should never

01:25:28.080 --> 01:25:30.850
talk about gender or race
or other social categories.

01:25:30.850 --> 01:25:32.460
In fact, the opposite.

01:25:32.460 --> 01:25:34.920
I believe we have to
start having conversations

01:25:34.920 --> 01:25:37.950
with even young children
about social categories,

01:25:37.950 --> 01:25:39.970
what they mean, and
what they don't mean.

01:25:39.970 --> 01:25:40.650
-Yeah.

01:25:40.650 --> 01:25:42.730
-The problem is children
have some real cognitive

01:25:42.730 --> 01:25:44.330
limitations.

01:25:44.330 --> 01:25:45.690
They are rigid classifiers.

01:25:45.690 --> 01:25:48.740
They make things very black and
white-- good, bad; boy, girl;

01:25:48.740 --> 01:25:50.150
mommies and daddies.

01:25:50.150 --> 01:25:53.110
And so once you
create the category

01:25:53.110 --> 01:25:55.400
and they build and construct
their own stereotypes,

01:25:55.400 --> 01:25:58.520
you're up against a big
wall, a lot of work.

01:25:58.520 --> 01:26:01.410
And I think this just means
that we have to, in schools,

01:26:01.410 --> 01:26:04.310
start having conversations
with children about gender,

01:26:04.310 --> 01:26:06.820
why it's a category, why
it's sometimes relevant,

01:26:06.820 --> 01:26:10.310
when it's not relevant, and
what gender stereotyping

01:26:10.310 --> 01:26:13.580
and prejudice mean as
early as kindergarten.

01:26:13.580 --> 01:26:14.630
-Yeah.

01:26:14.630 --> 01:26:15.130
Yeah.

01:26:17.900 --> 01:26:18.630
OK.

01:26:18.630 --> 01:26:21.340
I have to follow up in one
way because it's something

01:26:21.340 --> 01:26:22.543
I've seen as a parent.

01:26:25.120 --> 01:26:28.700
It seems to me, and
this is something

01:26:28.700 --> 01:26:33.820
that I see as a parent with
my kids and other kids,

01:26:33.820 --> 01:26:39.880
it is obviously OK and
we want to encourage it

01:26:39.880 --> 01:26:43.560
if a child feels
like it for someone

01:26:43.560 --> 01:26:45.680
who thinks he's a
boy to do girl things

01:26:45.680 --> 01:26:49.760
and dress up like a girl,
and of course vice versa.

01:26:49.760 --> 01:26:52.560
And of course, some kids
feel like neither or both.

01:26:52.560 --> 01:26:54.220
And even if you
think you're a boy,

01:26:54.220 --> 01:26:57.380
you can wear dresses and do
girl things and that's great.

01:26:57.380 --> 01:27:00.960
And we've had a lot of
support from the teachers

01:27:00.960 --> 01:27:02.800
who we've been lucky
enough to experience.

01:27:02.800 --> 01:27:08.320
But why is it not OK, in
a lot of circumstances,

01:27:08.320 --> 01:27:12.840
for white kids to pretend
to be Chinese or Apache?

01:27:12.840 --> 01:27:16.100
Why is that not cool?

01:27:16.100 --> 01:27:20.170
Do you get that with the very
salient comparison to race?

01:27:20.170 --> 01:27:25.490
And how do you answer that to
a six-year-old or to a teacher?

01:27:25.490 --> 01:27:25.990
-Yeah.

01:27:25.990 --> 01:27:28.370
Again, great
complicated questions,

01:27:28.370 --> 01:27:30.850
which require
conversations with children

01:27:30.850 --> 01:27:34.270
about social categories and
what they mean and don't mean.

01:27:34.270 --> 01:27:36.350
I will say that in
the lessons we do,

01:27:36.350 --> 01:27:39.350
I develop lessons
about sexism that we

01:27:39.350 --> 01:27:42.480
do with kids from kindergarten
through fifth grade.

01:27:42.480 --> 01:27:43.950
And one of the
lessons is there's

01:27:43.950 --> 01:27:46.490
no such thing as a boy's blank.

01:27:46.490 --> 01:27:48.840
There's no such thing
as a girl's backpack,

01:27:48.840 --> 01:27:51.520
shoes, hat, haircut, anything.

01:27:51.520 --> 01:27:54.220
And so part of the
lesson is saying

01:27:54.220 --> 01:27:56.510
you don't say it's OK for
boys to do girls things.

01:27:56.510 --> 01:27:58.593
It's saying there's no
such thing as a girl thing.

01:27:58.593 --> 01:28:01.390
There are just things and
anybody can do anything.

01:28:01.390 --> 01:28:04.990
But then you explain the idea
that some people do believe

01:28:04.990 --> 01:28:07.420
the "silly" idea that
there are girls' things,

01:28:07.420 --> 01:28:08.800
and here's what to say.

01:28:08.800 --> 01:28:11.580
We teach children to
chant, "I disagree.

01:28:11.580 --> 01:28:13.010
Sexism is silly to me."

01:28:13.010 --> 01:28:13.510
-Aww.

01:28:13.510 --> 01:28:16.890
-And they chant
that to each other.

01:28:16.890 --> 01:28:20.030
But then again, the
social categories

01:28:20.030 --> 01:28:22.180
vary in their history
and their treatment.

01:28:22.180 --> 01:28:24.510
And what requires is
constant education,

01:28:24.510 --> 01:28:27.670
then, about what is
offensive about white people

01:28:27.670 --> 01:28:30.240
doing things that are
traditionally associated

01:28:30.240 --> 01:28:35.530
with African American culture
or, as is common on campuses,

01:28:35.530 --> 01:28:37.970
seeing students pretending
to be blind for the day

01:28:37.970 --> 01:28:42.310
while they try to learn about
the experience of people

01:28:42.310 --> 01:28:44.440
who are visually impaired.

01:28:44.440 --> 01:28:46.330
-Yeah.

01:28:46.330 --> 01:28:47.600
Thank you.

01:28:47.600 --> 01:28:52.350
So I was hoping, Wesley,
if you wanted to--

01:28:52.350 --> 01:28:55.240
and I understand that this
may be one of the things

01:28:55.240 --> 01:28:58.250
where the right answer
would take too long,

01:28:58.250 --> 01:29:01.210
but if the right
answer can be given,

01:29:01.210 --> 01:29:04.420
if you could talk
more either about

01:29:04.420 --> 01:29:09.260
the differences among Native
American language groups

01:29:09.260 --> 01:29:11.890
and cultures in terms of third
genders and fourth genders--

01:29:11.890 --> 01:29:14.820
you mentioned that
patrilineal language groups

01:29:14.820 --> 01:29:18.810
and societies had much
less robust third gender

01:29:18.810 --> 01:29:20.740
and fourth gender
than matrilineal--

01:29:20.740 --> 01:29:28.810
or, if you prefer, the concept
of sexuality, of categorizing

01:29:28.810 --> 01:29:33.060
yourself by who you're into
rather than who you are,

01:29:33.060 --> 01:29:35.520
whether that has any
kind of parallels

01:29:35.520 --> 01:29:46.480
in any of the First Peoples
language groups that you /

01:29:46.480 --> 01:29:52.530
-In doing my research work using
my own language and my own home

01:29:52.530 --> 01:29:56.380
community, one
aspect of it, I was

01:29:56.380 --> 01:30:00.950
looking at the third gender
in a traditional setting.

01:30:00.950 --> 01:30:04.760
By the way, the
traditional way of life

01:30:04.760 --> 01:30:10.110
probably ended around 1930.

01:30:10.110 --> 01:30:15.940
Because by 1937, the
last living person

01:30:15.940 --> 01:30:20.770
who I would have
identified as third gender,

01:30:20.770 --> 01:30:24.750
she died in February of 1937.

01:30:24.750 --> 01:30:30.080
And since then, there's been
sheltering and shielding

01:30:30.080 --> 01:30:33.350
children within the
families because they've

01:30:33.350 --> 01:30:37.310
begun being ostracized
through the various Christian

01:30:37.310 --> 01:30:41.990
organizations that were saving
the Indians on reservations

01:30:41.990 --> 01:30:46.410
and of receiving a Western
education saying that doesn't

01:30:46.410 --> 01:30:48.870
meet the Western standards.

01:30:48.870 --> 01:30:52.110
So those people, some of them
were actually literally killed

01:30:52.110 --> 01:30:54.940
because of that.

01:30:54.940 --> 01:30:57.330
In my work in looking
at the relationship

01:30:57.330 --> 01:31:01.060
of the third gender,
for an example,

01:31:01.060 --> 01:31:06.730
it's a hetero gender,
meaning that the gender was

01:31:06.730 --> 01:31:09.550
a priority over their
sexual identity,

01:31:09.550 --> 01:31:12.550
and that between
the four genders

01:31:12.550 --> 01:31:19.270
back then-- the first gender is
a woman because she reproduces.

01:31:19.270 --> 01:31:23.570
The second gender is a
man who is a husband.

01:31:23.570 --> 01:31:26.040
Then the third
gender is basically

01:31:26.040 --> 01:31:29.470
biologically male
function as a woman,

01:31:29.470 --> 01:31:30.540
so that's a third gender.

01:31:30.540 --> 01:31:33.570
So Gender identity
there was feminine.

01:31:33.570 --> 01:31:36.670
And the fourth one is
a masculine gender.

01:31:36.670 --> 01:31:41.950
The relationship is between,
for an example, a first gender,

01:31:41.950 --> 01:31:44.900
is a woman, with
a fourth gender.

01:31:44.900 --> 01:31:49.360
First gender is feminine;
fourth gender is masculine.

01:31:49.360 --> 01:31:51.980
And the same thing with the men.

01:31:51.980 --> 01:31:55.770
The second gender would
have a relationship

01:31:55.770 --> 01:31:57.560
with the third gender.

01:31:57.560 --> 01:32:00.820
So it's opposite genders there,
even though biologically,

01:32:00.820 --> 01:32:02.170
they're the same.

01:32:02.170 --> 01:32:04.260
So that's one thing that
came out of this one.

01:32:04.260 --> 01:32:07.310
That was very normal,
I think, in a majority

01:32:07.310 --> 01:32:10.780
of the tribes in the
United States and Canada

01:32:10.780 --> 01:32:17.260
because you hear stories
of where in larger warring

01:32:17.260 --> 01:32:21.740
nations, they would
have a wife and they

01:32:21.740 --> 01:32:24.540
would acquire a second wife.

01:32:24.540 --> 01:32:26.890
And by that time, they
have a few children

01:32:26.890 --> 01:32:31.020
and they need somebody
who can provide

01:32:31.020 --> 01:32:33.550
some economic stability.

01:32:33.550 --> 01:32:37.030
So they would marry a third
wife who was a third gender.

01:32:37.030 --> 01:32:39.580
Third gender is
attributed with wealth,

01:32:39.580 --> 01:32:41.680
that they're the only
ones in most of the tribes

01:32:41.680 --> 01:32:44.160
where they could
accumulate wealth.

01:32:44.160 --> 01:32:46.840
If you were not in the third
gender category or fourth

01:32:46.840 --> 01:32:49.740
gender category, so if you
were the first or second one,

01:32:49.740 --> 01:32:52.010
you cannot accumulate wealth.

01:32:52.010 --> 01:32:54.420
That's equivalent to greed.

01:32:54.420 --> 01:32:56.920
When you acquire that,
you had to distribute that

01:32:56.920 --> 01:33:00.790
to your siblings and to
their offsprings and even

01:33:00.790 --> 01:33:02.030
your own children.

01:33:02.030 --> 01:33:03.406
You do not acquire that.

01:33:03.406 --> 01:33:04.780
So third gender
and fourth gender

01:33:04.780 --> 01:33:07.930
were the ones who could
be able to do that.

01:33:07.930 --> 01:33:14.530
And so they became second,
third, fourth spouses

01:33:14.530 --> 01:33:16.421
to provide an
economic stability.

01:33:22.410 --> 01:33:28.140
In one case, I know of
a man who was married,

01:33:28.140 --> 01:33:31.290
had a second wife who
was a third gender,

01:33:31.290 --> 01:33:33.560
and the first wife died.

01:33:33.560 --> 01:33:37.870
The third gender there
in that relationship

01:33:37.870 --> 01:33:40.620
picked up the responsibility
of raising the children.

01:33:43.270 --> 01:33:45.480
And that's one of the
things that we generally

01:33:45.480 --> 01:33:50.780
don't have in our language
is a word for "he" or "she."

01:33:50.780 --> 01:33:55.000
We just use gender terms,
a gender-based term

01:33:55.000 --> 01:33:57.820
in relationships,
like with children.

01:33:57.820 --> 01:34:04.925
[NAVAJO] is generally a
boy or [NAVAJO] is a girl.

01:34:04.925 --> 01:34:09.450
[NAVAJO] is a group of girls.

01:34:09.450 --> 01:34:14.040
[NAVAJO] is-- no. [NAVAJO]
is a group of girls.

01:34:14.040 --> 01:34:17.960
[NAVAJO] is a group of boys.

01:34:17.960 --> 01:34:25.870
And terms like [NAVAJO] "There's
an old man coming toward us."

01:34:25.870 --> 01:34:29.830
So it's a very gender based
language that we have.

01:34:29.830 --> 01:34:35.190
So there's really no
term describing his,

01:34:35.190 --> 01:34:39.430
hers, she, he, those
kind of terminologies.

01:34:39.430 --> 01:34:43.850
And I've always been
curious about that.

01:34:43.850 --> 01:34:46.510
But linguistic is
something that I mostly

01:34:46.510 --> 01:34:52.830
stumbled into after parading
through cultural anthropology

01:34:52.830 --> 01:34:54.250
for 30 years.

01:34:54.250 --> 01:34:54.750
-OK.

01:34:54.750 --> 01:34:58.630
-And now I'm heading up
the Navajo language program

01:34:58.630 --> 01:35:05.420
and just got an NSF grant and I
have to tackle that to look at.

01:35:05.420 --> 01:35:10.730
Generating verbs-- it's a
verb-based, like [NAVAJO] is

01:35:10.730 --> 01:35:14.460
more important, like [NAVAJO].

01:35:14.460 --> 01:35:18.890
It always ends with verb,
with a verb at the end.

01:35:18.890 --> 01:35:22.490
It's not the same as English
where there's a subject,

01:35:22.490 --> 01:35:24.610
then there's a
verb and an object.

01:35:24.610 --> 01:35:27.760
In our language, it's
subject, object, and verb.

01:35:27.760 --> 01:35:28.260
-OK.

01:35:28.260 --> 01:35:29.560
-So the verb is at the end.

01:35:29.560 --> 01:35:29.800
-Yeah.

