01:36:14.730 --> 01:36:16.870
But my question--
I was listening

01:36:16.870 --> 01:36:20.790
to the poet Alejandro
Zambra the other day,

01:36:20.790 --> 01:36:22.090
who's a Chilean poet.

01:36:22.090 --> 01:36:26.810
And in his remarks, he
mentioned how important

01:36:26.810 --> 01:36:31.470
it was for him that in
Spanish, objects are gendered.

01:36:31.470 --> 01:36:33.270
And as I'm sure
everybody here knows,

01:36:33.270 --> 01:36:36.320
in romance languages,
that's quite common,

01:36:36.320 --> 01:36:37.880
that everything is gendered.

01:36:37.880 --> 01:36:40.940
And of course it's
a binary gender.

01:36:40.940 --> 01:36:43.840
I mean, things are either
masculine or feminine.

01:36:43.840 --> 01:36:47.660
And he loves that as a poet.

01:36:47.660 --> 01:36:52.960
He loves thinking about a table
as being a masculine object

01:36:52.960 --> 01:36:55.920
and about a window as
being a feminine object

01:36:55.920 --> 01:36:58.550
and using that in his poetry.

01:36:58.550 --> 01:37:02.920
And I have no idea if there
are discussions of the kind

01:37:02.920 --> 01:37:06.480
that we're having
here among people

01:37:06.480 --> 01:37:09.800
who speak other languages
where gender is not

01:37:09.800 --> 01:37:14.600
so much about the person
as it is about the world

01:37:14.600 --> 01:37:16.451
that the person encounters.

01:37:16.451 --> 01:37:18.700
And I wondered if any of you
had any comments on that.

01:37:22.220 --> 01:37:26.180
-In my language, we have that.

01:37:26.180 --> 01:37:27.250
Hills are feminine.

01:37:33.640 --> 01:37:35.820
Rocky Mountains is masculine.

01:37:35.820 --> 01:37:40.080
The rain that comes with
thunder is masculine.

01:37:40.080 --> 01:37:44.040
The drizzle is feminine.

01:37:44.040 --> 01:37:47.660
Smooth the running
water is feminine.

01:37:47.660 --> 01:37:51.930
Rushing water, like through
the Grand Canyon, is masculine.

01:37:51.930 --> 01:37:54.370
We have plants
that are masculine.

01:37:54.370 --> 01:37:57.300
Ideas and thoughts
are genderized.

01:37:57.300 --> 01:38:00.610
Ceremonies are genderized.

01:38:00.610 --> 01:38:04.780
Behaviors are genderized,
despite being a woman

01:38:04.780 --> 01:38:09.290
and you're aggressive and you
go through that masculine stage

01:38:09.290 --> 01:38:12.500
and react from that.

01:38:12.500 --> 01:38:15.950
Your body, your left side
is masculine your right side

01:38:15.950 --> 01:38:18.590
is feminine.

01:38:18.590 --> 01:38:22.150
Your biological body
is-- if you're a man,

01:38:22.150 --> 01:38:25.200
it's supposedly
supposed to be male.

01:38:25.200 --> 01:38:29.700
But the inner side
of you is feminine.

01:38:29.700 --> 01:38:35.670
So there's that contrast
throughout the Navajo world.

01:38:38.320 --> 01:38:41.120
Smooth river rocks are feminine.

01:38:41.120 --> 01:38:45.910
Other rocks, hard ones with
sharp edges, are masculine.

01:38:45.910 --> 01:38:47.300
Flowers are like that.

01:38:47.300 --> 01:38:49.941
Even dirt is genderized.

01:38:49.941 --> 01:38:50.440
-Wow.

01:38:53.540 --> 01:38:56.520
If you're not a linguist and you
want to see someone explaining

01:38:56.520 --> 01:39:00.950
the research on gendered
nouns in romance languages

01:39:00.950 --> 01:39:04.700
and European languages, there's
a book by Guy Deutscher,

01:39:04.700 --> 01:39:10.860
D-E-U-T-S-C-H-E-R, which I was
hoping somebody would bring up,

01:39:10.860 --> 01:39:13.440
but I think I have to do it,
called Through the Language

01:39:13.440 --> 01:39:19.370
Glass, about what forms of the
Sapir-Whorf hypothesis are true

01:39:19.370 --> 01:39:21.420
and which ones are false.

01:39:21.420 --> 01:39:25.376
And that book, the last
chapter talks about the John

01:39:25.376 --> 01:39:26.750
[INAUDIBLE] stuff
about location.

01:39:26.750 --> 01:39:27.640
You probably know it.

01:39:27.640 --> 01:39:28.140
Yeah.

01:39:28.140 --> 01:39:31.270
The second to last chapter
talks about a very, very large

01:39:31.270 --> 01:39:34.120
psych department-y
study of gendered nouns

01:39:34.120 --> 01:39:36.000
in German and gendered
nouns in French.

01:39:36.000 --> 01:39:39.280
And it turns out that if you do
a very good academic psychology

01:39:39.280 --> 01:39:41.410
study with people
clicking buttons

01:39:41.410 --> 01:39:43.300
to see what their
reaction times are,

01:39:43.300 --> 01:39:46.580
that if you speak a
language where a bridge is

01:39:46.580 --> 01:39:50.570
a feminine noun, you will
have a slight propensity

01:39:50.570 --> 01:39:52.660
to think that
bridges are welcoming

01:39:52.660 --> 01:39:54.640
and forgiving and soft.

01:39:54.640 --> 01:39:56.990
And if in your language
bridge is a masculine noun,

01:39:56.990 --> 01:39:58.900
you'll think of them
as hard and tough.

01:39:58.900 --> 01:39:59.947
Not much, but a little.

01:39:59.947 --> 01:40:02.030
So there is research on
that in romance languages.

01:40:02.030 --> 01:40:02.529
-OK.

01:40:02.529 --> 01:40:03.240
Thank you.

